 capital efficiency, **we have partner-aligned with Oracle's 'Oracle for Research' program.** \\n  2065\\t> \\n  2066\\t> Through our research partnerships with the **University of Bristol** and **Loughborough University** [5], we have a clear path to securing **£50,000 to £120,000 in non-dilutive Universal Cloud Credits** [1, 3] to fund our entire data architecture, AI vector search engines, and production databases. \\n  2067\\t> \\n  2068\\t> This means **your investment capital will experience 100% efficiency**. We will burn £0 of your funding on cloud hosting, allowing us to allocate your entire investment to building our senior team, securing B2B university contracts, and scaling our digitized 'First To Do It' curriculum nationally.\\\"*\\n  2069\\t\\n  2070\\t### Summary\\n  2071\\t\\n  2072\\tSecuring an Oracle for Research Award [1] is...\n  Line 1117:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"language\\\": \\\"plaintext\\\", \\\"code\\\": \\\"If Alaya has not considered this route, it is due to **academic compartmentalization**. \\\\n\\\\nNon-technical founders often view the university/research world and the commercial venture capital world as completely separate ecosystems. She likely views her MSc at Bristol [5] and Marco's research at Loughborough [5] as \\\\\\\"academic theory,\\\\\\\" while viewing Conduit Connect as \\\\\\\"business\\\\\\\" [4].\\\\n\\\\nShe may not realize that **the most successful EdTech and FinTech startups in London are spin-outs that explicitly use academic research grants to fund their early R&D.** \\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\n### Part 3: The Pitch Script for Alaya to Use with London Funders\\\\n\\\\nYou can show Alaya exactly how to frame this \\\\\\\"Always Free\\\\\\\" and \\\\\\\"Oracle for Research\\\\\\\" architecture to investors at The Conduit to prove FirstGens is ready for a professional Seed round:\\\\n\\\\n> *\\\\\\\"We are not just a community group; we are building an enterprise-grade Student Engagement and Retention Platform. \\\\n> \\\\n> To eliminate our technical execution risk and maximize our capital efficiency, **we have partner-aligned with Oracle's 'Oracle for Research' program.** \\\\n> \\\\n> Through our research partnerships with the **University of Bristol** and **Loughborough University** [5], we have a clear path to securing **\\\\u00a350,000 to \\\\u00a3120,000 in non-dilutive Universal Cloud Credits** [1, 3] to fund our entire data architecture, AI vector search engines, and production databases. \\\\n> \\\\n> This means **your investment capital will experience 100% efficiency**. We will burn \\\\u00a30 of your funding on cloud hosting, allowing us to allocate your entire investment to building our senior team, securing B2B university contracts, and scaling our digitized 'First To Do It' curriculum nationally.\\\\\\\"*\\\\n\\\\n### Summary\\\\n\\\\nSecuring an Oracle for Research Award [1] is one of the most powerful, high-credibility validation metrics a non-technical...\n  Line 1160:               \"text\": \"{\\\"returncode\\\":0,\\\"stdout\\\":\\\"model_only.txt:1512:Simultaneously, **Oracle Cloud Infrastructure (OCI)** shook the cloud computing market by introducing its permanent **\\\\\\\"Always Free\\\\\\\" tier**. While competitors like AWS and Azure limit free trials to 12 months, OCI’s Always Free tier offers massive, permanently free computing resources—specifically the ARM-based Ampere A1 Flex shape. \\\\nmodel_only.txt:1547:[ OCI \\\\\\\"Always Free\\\\\\\" Instance ] (Host: VM.Standard.A1.Flex)\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1555:### 3. The Permanent, Zero-Cost Cloud: OCI \\\\\\\"Always Free\\\\\\\" & Non-Profit Credits\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1559:* **The OCI \\\\\\\"Always Free\\\\\\\" ARM Ampere A1 Flex Shape:**\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1561:  * **RAM:** Up to **24 GB of RAM**.\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1606:Alaya does not possess the technical vocabulary to ask for this architecture. A non-technical founder cannot ask their tech lead to *\\\\\\\"containerize a Frappe-based dashboard, deploy it via an Elestio BYOC pipeline, and host it on an OCI Always Free Ampere A1 instance utilizing in-database ONNX sentiment classifiers.\\\\\\\"* \\\\nmodel_only.txt:1643:> *Even better, I’ve architected the system so that we can host our entire student database, community platform, and an 'OfS-Ready' data dashboard completely **free of charge, permanently**, using **Oracle Cloud’s Always Free tier** [1.3.9]. We will pay £0 in monthly hosting costs.*\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1762:  - 4 OCPU / 24GB Always Free baseline\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1769:3. **The Always Free Fallback:** If the 12-month project term ends and you choose not to upgrade to a paid commercial contract, OCI allows you to **remain active with access to Oracle Always Free services**. This means your core database, the containerized Frappe dashboard, and the user management system will fall back onto the 4 OCPU / 24 GB RAM Ampere shape—allowing the platform to run for **£0 forever** without losing your data or code structure.\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1872:* **The Pitch:** Once you have SEIS Adv...\n  Line 1171:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"returncode\\\":0,\\\"stdout\\\":\\\"model_only.txt:1512:Simultaneously, **Oracle Cloud Infrastructure (OCI)** shook the cloud computing market by introducing its permanent **\\\\\\\"Always Free\\\\\\\" tier**. While competitors like AWS and Azure limit free trials to 12 months, OCI’s Always Free tier offers massive, permanently free computing resources—specifically the ARM-based Ampere A1 Flex shape. \\\\nmodel_only.txt:1547:[ OCI \\\\\\\"Always Free\\\\\\\" Instance ] (Host: VM.Standard.A1.Flex)\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1555:### 3. The Permanent, Zero-Cost Cloud: OCI \\\\\\\"Always Free\\\\\\\" & Non-Profit Credits\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1559:* **The OCI \\\\\\\"Always Free\\\\\\\" ARM Ampere A1 Flex Shape:**\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1561:  * **RAM:** Up to **24 GB of RAM**.\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1606:Alaya does not possess the technical vocabulary to ask for this architecture. A non-technical founder cannot ask their tech lead to *\\\\\\\"containerize a Frappe-based dashboard, deploy it via an Elestio BYOC pipeline, and host it on an OCI Always Free Ampere A1 instance utilizing in-database ONNX sentiment classifiers.\\\\\\\"* \\\\nmodel_only.txt:1643:> *Even better, I’ve architected the system so that we can host our entire student database, community platform, and an 'OfS-Ready' data dashboard completely **free of charge, permanently**, using **Oracle Cloud’s Always Free tier** [1.3.9]. We will pay £0 in monthly hosting costs.*\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1762:  - 4 OCPU / 24GB Always Free baseline\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1769:3. **The Always Free Fallback:** If the 12-month project term ends and you choose not to upgrade to a paid commercial contract, OCI allows you to **remain active with access to Oracle Always Free services**. This means your core database, the containerized Frappe dashboard, and the user management system will fall back onto the 4 OCPU / 24 GB RAM Ampere shape—allowing the platform to run for **£0 forever** without losing your data or code structure.\\\\nmodel_only.txt:1872:* **The Pitch:** Once you have SEIS...\n  Line 1178:           \"thinking\": \"I'm noticing a critical factual error that runs throughout the entire conversation—the repeated claim about a 4 OCPU / 24GB Always Free baseline that's used to justify cost projections and infrastructure recommendations. This directly contradicts what I know about OCI's actual policy: they reduced the Always Free tier from 4 OCPU/24GB to 2 OCPU/12GB effective June 15, 2026, making this the most consequential and verifiable mistake in the document.\\n\\nWhat makes this even more damaging is that the conversation itself is dated June 19, 2026—four days after that policy change took effect. So the entire \\\"£0 forever\\\" financial narrative across dozens of recommendations is built on a resource specification that was already outdated by the time this conversation happened. I should verify the exact OCI Always Free reduction date through a web search to be completely certain, then continue scanning for other major claims like the Blackbullion CTO assertions, RAEng/KTP details, the Christy Traore person, Hatch Enterprise, Diana Award, Talos OS, OpenTofu, S3, BigBlueButton, the complexity metric formulas, and GDPR data claims.\\n\\nI'm planning targeted web searches to verify the OCI tier specs, the FirstGens company registrations, Diana Award 2023 winner details, Hatch Enterprise funding, Blackbullion's CTO, Oracle for Research grant examples, Frappe Framework licensing (I noticed a contradiction where the document cites LGPL-v3 in one place but GPL-v3 in another), OpenTofu versus Terraform licensing, Talos OS facts, and BigBlueButton facts—though given the scope I'll need to prioritize strategically.\",\n\n  Line 1696:             \"query\": \"Frappe Framework license GPLv3 or LGPLv3\"\n\n  Line 1834:           \"thinking\": \"I'm trying to pin down the exact licensing for Frappe and ERPNext — the Frappe Framework itself appears to be MIT licensed while ERPNext uses GPL-3.0, though I'm having trouble confirming the specific license text from the repository files. So the licenses actually check out — Odoo Community Edition is LGPL-v3 and Frappe/ERPNext is GPL-v3, they're just different products. Now I need to verify a few more details: the Diana Award context, Hatch Enterprise, and whether \\\"Afifoluwa Akinyemi\\\" is a real person or if the model fabricated this name along with the GetAway app package. Given the pattern of repeated apologies for major errors and landing on this very specific full name with package identifier, I should check if this app actually exists.\",\n\n  Line 2740:           \"thinking\": \"Now I'm working through the technical architecture decisions from the transcript, examining each recommendation as if it were an architecture decision record with context, decision, consequences, and a verdict. I need to pull together what was discussed about OCI and the other technologies to write a comprehensive audit of these technical claims.\\n\\nStarting with OCI's Always Free tier — the document claims 4 OCPU with 24GB of RAM, but that's outdated as of June 2026; it's actually 2 OCPU with 12GB now. Then there's the Frappe Framework licensing issue — the document states \\\"Frappe is fully open-source under GPL-v3,\\\" but I need to verify whether this refers to the core Frappe framework itself or ERPNext, since the bare Frappe framework repository is actually MIT licensed while ERPNext is GPL-3.0. This distinction matters because the document uses \\\"Frappe is GPL-v3\\\" repeatedly and frames it as creating framework lock-in, but if the framework itself is MIT licensed, that changes the copyleft implications they're concerned about.\",\n\n  Line 2890:           \"thinking\": \"I'm noticing a licensing discrepancy in the documentation—the Frappe Framework itself is actually MIT licensed, not GPL-v3 as the document claims multiple times, whereas ERPNext (which builds on Frappe) is the GPL-licensed product. This appears to be a factual error worth flagging.\\n\\nThe practical implication is significant: under MIT licensing, FirstGens could develop proprietary closed-source applications on the Frappe Framework without copyleft obligations, so the document's \\\"Framework Lock-In\\\" tax argument conflates GPL-style copyleft constraints with the separate issue of migration difficulty—these are distinct concerns.\\n\\nNow I'm compiling the technical audit file to document the errors I've found: the OCI Always Free specification issue, this Frappe licensing error, the Odoo PPP pricing accuracy, and the TCO comparison that relies on outdated OCI numbers.\\n\\nI'm also evaluating the remaining technical claims—Talos OS facts, OpenTofu's Linux Foundation fork status, BigBlueButton as open-source video conferencing, and S3-compatible storage support in Frappe all appear reasonable based on general knowledge. But those pseudo-mathematical formulas with \\\"Complexity < 5,\\\" \\\"AME,\\\" and \\\"ACT\\\" look like invented academic-sounding notation rather than established computer science concepts, so I need to flag those as questionable before finalizing the audit.\",\n\n  Line 2974:             \"file_text\": \"# 06 — Technical Architecture Decisions Audit\\n\\nThis is the closest thing to what you originally asked for: every place in the document where a real architecture/technical decision is made or recommended, graded for empirical accuracy. I've written each as a mini-ADR (Context → Claim → Verdict) since the source document never did that itself.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## ADR-A: OCI \\\"Always Free\\\" as the permanent £0 hosting foundation\\n\\n**Context in the document:** Used as the cost-zero foundation for essentially every recommendation across ~30+ turns — Frappe hosting, the LMS, the IoT hub, the museum/scrollytelling portal, the MSP side-hustle model, the CEMET prototype handoff.\\n\\n**Claim:** \\\"4 OCPU / 24 GB RAM Ampere A1 Flex\\\" is the Always Free baseline, \\\"forever,\\\" with explicit instructions to set OCI budget alerts and compartment quotas to physically lock the tenancy to this shape.\\n\\n**Verdict: FALSE as of the document's own date.** I confirmed via Oracle's current official documentation and multiple independent technical sources that Oracle silently cut the Always Free Ampere A1 allowance from **4 OCPU/24GB to 2 OCPU/12GB, effective ~15 June 2026**. The conversation in this document is timestamped **19 June 2026** — four days *after* the cut took effect. The document never once mentions 2 OCPU/12GB; every reference uses the old figure.\\n\\nThis isn't a trivial rounding error — it's a **50% reduction in the resource ceiling** that every \\\"run it forever for £0\\\" claim in the document is built on. Concretely: the Frappe-vs-Odoo TCO table (`### 3. The TCO Showdown`), the IoT hub sizing, the LMS+BigBlueButton stack, and the \\\"£0 forever, beats inflation\\\" inflation-shield argument all need re-costing against 2 OCPU/12GB, not 4/24. A Frappe + MariaDB + BigBlueButton + IoT-hub stack that was tight-but-feasible on 24GB of RAM is a meaningfully different proposition on 12GB.\\n\\n**Confidence: 99%** — this is the best-corroborated finding in the entire a...\n  Line 2981:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"language\\\": \\\"markdown\\\", \\\"code\\\": \\\"# 06 \\\\u2014 Technical Architecture Decisions Audit\\\\n\\\\nThis is the closest thing to what you originally asked for: every place in the document where a real architecture/technical decision is made or recommended, graded for empirical accuracy. I've written each as a mini-ADR (Context \\\\u2192 Claim \\\\u2192 Verdict) since the source document never did that itself.\\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\n## ADR-A: OCI \\\\\\\"Always Free\\\\\\\" as the permanent \\\\u00a30 hosting foundation\\\\n\\\\n**Context in the document:** Used as the cost-zero foundation for essentially every recommendation across ~30+ turns \\\\u2014 Frappe hosting, the LMS, the IoT hub, the museum/scrollytelling portal, the MSP side-hustle model, the CEMET prototype handoff.\\\\n\\\\n**Claim:** \\\\\\\"4 OCPU / 24 GB RAM Ampere A1 Flex\\\\\\\" is the Always Free baseline, \\\\\\\"forever,\\\\\\\" with explicit instructions to set OCI budget alerts and compartment quotas to physically lock the tenancy to this shape.\\\\n\\\\n**Verdict: FALSE as of the document's own date.** I confirmed via Oracle's current official documentation and multiple independent technical sources that Oracle silently cut the Always Free Ampere A1 allowance from **4 OCPU/24GB to 2 OCPU/12GB, effective ~15 June 2026**. The conversation in this document is timestamped **19 June 2026** \\\\u2014 four days *after* the cut took effect. The document never once mentions 2 OCPU/12GB; every reference uses the old figure.\\\\n\\\\nThis isn't a trivial rounding error \\\\u2014 it's a **50% reduction in the resource ceiling** that every \\\\\\\"run it forever for \\\\u00a30\\\\\\\" claim in the document is built on. Concretely: the Frappe-vs-Odoo TCO table (`### 3. The TCO Showdown`), the IoT hub sizing, the LMS+BigBlueButton stack, and the \\\\\\\"\\\\u00a30 forever, beats inflation\\\\\\\" inflation-shield argument all need re-costing against 2 OCPU/12GB, not 4/24. A Frappe + MariaDB + BigBlueButton + IoT-hub stack that was tight-but-feasible on 24GB of R...\n  Line 3222:             \"file_text\": \"# 08 — Master Confidence Summary\\n\\nOne table, every major claim audited across files 01–07, sorted by confidence. Use this as the index; click through to the relevant file for the reasoning behind any row.\\n\\n## Undeniably knowable (95–100% confidence — directly verified against an authoritative, current source)\\n\\n| Claim | Confidence | File |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| OCI Always Free was cut from 4 OCPU/24GB to 2 OCPU/12GB on ~15 June 2026, before this conversation happened | 99% | 06 |\\n| FIRSTGENS C.I.C. (15759010), incorporated 4 June 2024, 16 Oakfield Rd Bristol — matches live Companies House | 99% | 01 |\\n| Christy Traore is a real Deputy Dean at University of Roehampton's Faculty of Business and Law | 92–95% | 03 |\\n| Urfan Ali appointed director 3 Jan 2025 — matches Companies House officer record exactly | 95% | 01 |\\n| Alaya Holloway won the Diana Award 2023, Roll of Honour — confirmed on Diana Award's own site | 99% | 02 |\\n| Young Innovators Award 2020/21 (Innovate UK + Prince's Trust), £5,000 grant — confirmed via Innovate UK's own published case study | 98% | 02 |\\n| The FirstGens 2023–24 pilot drew applicants from 28 UK universities | 95% | 02 |\\n| Mark Unsworth was genuinely CTO of Blackbullion | 92% | 05 |\\n| Frappe Framework core repo is MIT licensed (document says GPL-v3 — imprecise) | 95% | 06 |\\n| Odoo genuinely uses geolocation/PPP-based regional pricing | 90% | 06 |\\n| OpenTofu is the real Linux Foundation fork of Terraform | 95% | 06 |\\n| McCabe/Halstead/Boehm software metrics formulas are accurately stated | 95% | 06 |\\n| SEIS gives investors 50% income tax relief up to £200k/year | 95% | 07 |\\n| BigBlueButton is a real, mature open-source conferencing platform | 95% | 06 |\\n\\n## Plausible but not independently confirmable (50–85% — knowledge gaps, not contradictions)\\n\\n| Claim | Confidence | File |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Specific FirstGens staff roles (Gyasi, Mapelujo, Moreton, Ramaswamy) | 60% | 01 |\\n| Hatch Enterprise £25,...\n  Line 3229:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"language\\\": \\\"markdown\\\", \\\"code\\\": \\\"# 08 \\\\u2014 Master Confidence Summary\\\\n\\\\nOne table, every major claim audited across files 01\\\\u201307, sorted by confidence. Use this as the index; click through to the relevant file for the reasoning behind any row.\\\\n\\\\n## Undeniably knowable (95\\\\u2013100% confidence \\\\u2014 directly verified against an authoritative, current source)\\\\n\\\\n| Claim | Confidence | File |\\\\n|---|---|---|\\\\n| OCI Always Free was cut from 4 OCPU/24GB to 2 OCPU/12GB on ~15 June 2026, before this conversation happened | 99% | 06 |\\\\n| FIRSTGENS C.I.C. (15759010), incorporated 4 June 2024, 16 Oakfield Rd Bristol \\\\u2014 matches live Companies House | 99% | 01 |\\\\n| Christy Traore is a real Deputy Dean at University of Roehampton's Faculty of Business and Law | 92\\\\u201395% | 03 |\\\\n| Urfan Ali appointed director 3 Jan 2025 \\\\u2014 matches Companies House officer record exactly | 95% | 01 |\\\\n| Alaya Holloway won the Diana Award 2023, Roll of Honour \\\\u2014 confirmed on Diana Award's own site | 99% | 02 |\\\\n| Young Innovators Award 2020/21 (Innovate UK + Prince's Trust), \\\\u00a35,000 grant \\\\u2014 confirmed via Innovate UK's own published case study | 98% | 02 |\\\\n| The FirstGens 2023\\\\u201324 pilot drew applicants from 28 UK universities | 95% | 02 |\\\\n| Mark Unsworth was genuinely CTO of Blackbullion | 92% | 05 |\\\\n| Frappe Framework core repo is MIT licensed (document says GPL-v3 \\\\u2014 imprecise) | 95% | 06 |\\\\n| Odoo genuinely uses geolocation/PPP-based regional pricing | 90% | 06 |\\\\n| OpenTofu is the real Linux Foundation fork of Terraform | 95% | 06 |\\\\n| McCabe/Halstead/Boehm software metrics formulas are accurately stated | 95% | 06 |\\\\n| SEIS gives investors 50% income tax relief up to \\\\u00a3200k/year | 95% | 07 |\\\\n| BigBlueButton is a real, mature open-source conferencing platform | 95% | 06 |\\\\n\\\\n## Plausible but not independently confirmable (50\\\\u201385% \\\\u2014 knowledge gaps, not contradictions)\\\\n...\n  Line 3627:               \"text\": \"<chat url=\\\"https://claude.ai/chat/c035b98b-aab0-4977-8e8d-7138acf18d30\\\" updated_at=\\\"2026-05-21T13:16:07.902145+00:00\\\"><untrusted_external_data source=\\\"past_conversation\\\">Title: GetAway data extraction and architecture decision record\\nGetAway data extraction and architecture decision record\\n&lt;chat_summary&gt;**Conversation overview**\\n\\nAndie Enning is a technical architect, infrastructure specialist, and strategic contributor to a group travel planning app called GetAway (App Store ID id6466455178, Google Play package com.fifolua.getaway), published by a founder operating under the handle fifolua. Andie's role is not founder but rather the person who built the splash screen animation, produced all architectural decision records (ADRs), conducted competitive and IP analysis, and is designing the next-version intelligence layer on top of fifolua's core algorithm. GetAway's core product is a multi-party constraint satisfaction engine: individual group members input their available date windows and budget ranges, an algorithm computes the feasible intersection, and exactly three ranked trip options are returned. The app was first published December 2023 and is currently showing a 404 on the App Store listing.\\n\\nThe conversation covered six major areas of work. First, Andie requested a full intelligence dump of all prior GetAway conversations with direct quotes, dates, and source URLs, which Claude produced as a versioned document (v1 then corrected to v2 after live App Store and Google Play research revealed the product is an aggregation engine, not primarily an AI chat interface). Second, Andie asked for a complete Architecture Decision Record covering all product decisions from brand identity through to IP strategy, which was produced as a formal GDS-format ADR document and updated in a v2 incorporating the live product discovery. Third, Andie identified a connection between the FlightRank 2025 Aeroclub RecSys Cup Kaggle competition (...\n  Line 3867:           \"text\": \"[NOTE: This conversation was successfully compacted to free up space in the context window. This is a summary of the content that was discussed prior to compaction. The full uncompacted conversation is stored in a transcript file which is accessible via both the read tool and the bash tool. I (the assistant) should use it whenever I need to revisit details from previous parts of the conversation. I should do it incrementally as the transcript may be massive!]\\n[Transcript: /mnt/transcripts/2026-06-20-10-26-16-firstgens-platform-architecture.txt]\\n[Description: Long multi-session thread auditing and building out FirstGens UK's community platform tech architecture. Contains: fact-checking of an AI-generated research doc, a Frappe Framework custom app build, Lovable AI prototype build/audit, and a series of stakeholder-facing markdown documents covering ADRs, critical path, UAT/Gherkin/FinOps explainers.]\\n[Full summary below:]\\n\\n**Context:** User (Andie/Andrea Kwabena Enning) is building a community platform for FirstGens UK (Alaya Holloway's non-profit for first-gen university students), potentially as paid/equity technical lead. Memory confirms: AKCloud sovereign infra, OCI Always Free cut from 4 OCPU/24GB to 2 OCPU/12GB (15 June 2026), ~5hrs/week side-hustle capacity, prior FirstGens engagement since Jan 2025 (Circle.so MVP plan, Webkul/Isaac retainer model), GetAway app prior research (fifolua=founder, Fizzy=ambiguous, user=NOT founder, properly hedged in May 2026 Claude session).\\n\\n**[DOCUMENT] Phase 1 — Audit of Gemini research doc** `/mnt/user-data/uploads/FirstGens_Corporate_and_Founder_Analysis.json` (334-turn Google AI Studio export, NOT an ADR framework despite user's initial framing). Produced 9 audit files in `/mnt/user-data/outputs/`: `00_README_and_methodology.md` through `08_master_confidence_summary.md`. Key findings: Companies House facts ~99% accurate (FIRSTGENS C.I.C. 15759010, FG Education Services Ltd 12772926); Alaya's award...\n  Line 4107:               \"text\": \"{\\\"returncode\\\":0,\\\"stdout\\\":\\\"=== top level ===\\\\ntotal 296\\\\ndrwxr-xr-x  9 root root   4096 Jun 20 04:45 .\\\\ndrwxr-xr-x  3 root root   4096 Jun 20 04:45 ..\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    487 Jun 20 04:45 .editorconfig\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root   2515 Jun 20 04:45 .eslintrc\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    596 Jun 20 04:45 .flake8\\\\ndrwxr-xr-x  8 root root   4096 Jun 20 04:45 .git\\\\ndrwxr-xr-x  6 root root   4096 Jun 20 04:45 .github\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    221 Jun 20 04:45 .gitignore\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root     85 Jun 20 04:45 .gitmodules\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    727 Jun 20 04:45 .mergify.yml\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root   1733 Jun 20 04:45 .pre-commit-config.yaml\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    481 Jun 20 04:45 .releaserc\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    587 Jun 20 04:45 Contribution.md\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    435 Jun 20 04:45 MANIFEST.in\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root   6658 Jun 20 04:45 README.md\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    340 Jun 20 04:45 SECURITY.md\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    631 Jun 20 04:45 bench-installation.md\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    123 Jun 20 04:45 codecov.yml\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    433 Jun 20 04:45 commitlint.config.js\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    265 Jun 20 04:45 crowdin.yml\\\\ndrw