t root    433 Jun 20 04:45 commitlint.config.js\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    265 Jun 20 04:45 crowdin.yml\\\\ndrwxr-xr-x  5 root root   4096 Jun 20 04:45 cypress\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root    618 Jun 20 04:45 cypress.config.js\\\\ndrwxr-xr-x  2 root root   4096 Jun 20 04:45 docker\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root   1447 Jun 20 04:45 docker-installation.md\\\\ndrwxr-xr-x  2 root root   4096 Jun 20 04:45 frappe-ui\\\\ndrwxr-xr-x  4 root root   4096 Jun 20 04:45 frontend\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root  33893 Jun 20 04:45 license.txt\\\\ndrwxr-xr-x 15 root root   4096 Jun 20 04:45 lms\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root   1039 Jun 20 04:45 package.json\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root   2130 Jun 20 04:45 pyproject.toml\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root      0 Jun 20 04:45 yarn-error.log\\\\n-rw-r--r--  1 root root 141847 Jun 20 04:45 yarn.lock\\\\n\\\\n=== README head ===\\\\n<div align=\\\\\\\"center\\\\\\\" markd...\n  Line 4125:           \"thinking\": \"The package.json confirms it—Frappe LMS is built on Vue 3 with vue-router and pinia for state management, along with frappe-ui as a core dependency. The license is AGPL-3.0-or-later, not GPL-3.\\n\\n0 like the broader Frappe Framework, which is a notable distinction. Now I'm diving into the backend data model by examining the DocType definitions in the lms directory to understand the actual structure—Course, Batch, Chapter, Lesson, Quiz, Certificate, and other entities that will shape the boilerplate architecture.\",\n\n  Line 4215:               \"text\": \"{\\\"returncode\\\":0,\\\"stdout\\\":\\\"lms_course_interest\\\\nlms_course_mentor_mapping\\\\nlms_course_progress\\\\nlms_course_review\\\\nlms_enrollment\\\\nlms_google_meet_settings\\\\nlms_job_application\\\\nlms_lesson_note\\\\nlms_live_class\\\\nlms_live_class_participant\\\\nlms_option\\\\nlms_payment\\\\nlms_program\\\\nlms_program_course\\\\nlms_program_member\\\\nlms_programming_exercise\\\\nlms_programming_exercise_submission\\\\nlms_question\\\\nlms_quiz\\\\nlms_quiz_question\\\\nlms_quiz_result\\\\nlms_quiz_submission\\\\nlms_settings\\\\nlms_sidebar_item\\\\nlms_source\\\\nlms_test_case\\\\nlms_test_case_submission\\\\nlms_timetable_legend\\\\nlms_timetable_template\\\\nlms_video_watch_duration\\\\nlms_zoom_settings\\\\npayment_country\\\\npreferred_function\\\\npreferred_industry\\\\nrelated_courses\\\\nscheduled_flow\\\\nskills\\\\nuser_skill\\\\nwork_experience\\\\nzoom_settings\\\\n\\\\n=== look for discussion/community/mentor docs specifically ===\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_program_member\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_program_member/lms_program_member.py\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_program_member/lms_program_member.json\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_course_mentor_mapping\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_course_mentor_mapping/test_lms_course_mentor_mapping.py\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_course_mentor_mapping/lms_course_mentor_mapping.json\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_course_mentor_mapping/lms_course_mentor_mapping.py\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_course_mentor_mapping/lms_course_mentor_mapping.js\\\\n\\\\n=== hooks.py (first 80 lines) ===\\\\nimport frappe\\\\n\\\\nfrom . import __version__ as app_version\\\\n\\\\napp_name = \\\\\\\"frappe_lms\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_title = \\\\\\\"Learning\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_publisher = \\\\\\\"Frappe\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_description = \\\\\\\"Open Source Learning Management System built with Frappe Framework\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_icon_url = \\\\\\\"/assets/lms/images/lms-logo.png\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_icon_title = \\\\\\\"Learning\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_icon_route = \\\\\\\"/lms\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_color = \\\\\\\"grey\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_email = \\\\\\\"jannat@frappe.io\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_license = \\\\\\\"AGPL\\\\\\\"\\\\nrequired_apps = [\\\\\\\"frappe/payments\\\\\\\"]\\\\n\\\\n\\\\ndef get_lms_path():\\\\n\\\\tpath = \\\\\\\"l...\n  Line 4226:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"returncode\\\":0,\\\"stdout\\\":\\\"lms_course_interest\\\\nlms_course_mentor_mapping\\\\nlms_course_progress\\\\nlms_course_review\\\\nlms_enrollment\\\\nlms_google_meet_settings\\\\nlms_job_application\\\\nlms_lesson_note\\\\nlms_live_class\\\\nlms_live_class_participant\\\\nlms_option\\\\nlms_payment\\\\nlms_program\\\\nlms_program_course\\\\nlms_program_member\\\\nlms_programming_exercise\\\\nlms_programming_exercise_submission\\\\nlms_question\\\\nlms_quiz\\\\nlms_quiz_question\\\\nlms_quiz_result\\\\nlms_quiz_submission\\\\nlms_settings\\\\nlms_sidebar_item\\\\nlms_source\\\\nlms_test_case\\\\nlms_test_case_submission\\\\nlms_timetable_legend\\\\nlms_timetable_template\\\\nlms_video_watch_duration\\\\nlms_zoom_settings\\\\npayment_country\\\\npreferred_function\\\\npreferred_industry\\\\nrelated_courses\\\\nscheduled_flow\\\\nskills\\\\nuser_skill\\\\nwork_experience\\\\nzoom_settings\\\\n\\\\n=== look for discussion/community/mentor docs specifically ===\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_program_member\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_program_member/lms_program_member.py\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_program_member/lms_program_member.json\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_course_mentor_mapping\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_course_mentor_mapping/test_lms_course_mentor_mapping.py\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_course_mentor_mapping/lms_course_mentor_mapping.json\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_course_mentor_mapping/lms_course_mentor_mapping.py\\\\n./lms/doctype/lms_course_mentor_mapping/lms_course_mentor_mapping.js\\\\n\\\\n=== hooks.py (first 80 lines) ===\\\\nimport frappe\\\\n\\\\nfrom . import __version__ as app_version\\\\n\\\\napp_name = \\\\\\\"frappe_lms\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_title = \\\\\\\"Learning\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_publisher = \\\\\\\"Frappe\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_description = \\\\\\\"Open Source Learning Management System built with Frappe Framework\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_icon_url = \\\\\\\"/assets/lms/images/lms-logo.png\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_icon_title = \\\\\\\"Learning\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_icon_route = \\\\\\\"/lms\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_color = \\\\\\\"grey\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_email = \\\\\\\"jannat@frappe.io\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_license = \\\\\\\"AGPL\\\\\\\"\\\\nrequired_apps = [\\\\\\\"frappe/payments\\\\\\\"]\\\\n\\\\n\\\\ndef get_lms_path():\\\\n\\\\tpath = \\...\n  Line 4312:           \"text\": \"Good — I have the real upstream confirmed: Frappe LMS frontend is genuinely Vue 3 + Pinia + Vue Router + `frappe-ui` (license is AGPL-3.0, not the MIT/GPL split I flagged earlier — that's specific to the LMS app, separate from the core Frappe framework). It covers courses, batches, certificates, mentorship — but it has **no discussion/feed/spaces layer**, which is the actual core of what Circle.io does. So the real architecture is: install `frappe/lms` unmodified for the course layer, and build a thin custom app on top for the community layer Circle.io is actually known for. Building that now, plus the Gherkin specs and the AI extension hooks.\",\n\n  Line 4617:             \"file_text\": \"# Copyright (c) 2026, AndieKobbieTech Solutions (AKT) and contributors\\n# For license information, please see license.txt\\nimport frappe\\nfrom frappe.model.document import Document\\n\\n\\nclass FGPost(Document):\\n\\tdef before_insert(self):\\n\\t\\tspace = frappe.get_doc(\\\"FG Space\\\", self.space)\\n\\t\\tif space.requires_approval_to_post and not self.has_permission(\\\"write\\\"):\\n\\t\\t\\tself.is_approved = 0\\n\\n\\tdef on_trash(self):\\n\\t\\t# Cascade-delete comments so the feed doesn't show orphaned replies.\\n\\t\\tfrappe.db.delete(\\\"FG Comment\\\", {\\\"post\\\": self.name})\\n\",\n\n  Line 4624:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"language\\\": \\\"python\\\", \\\"code\\\": \\\"# Copyright (c) 2026, AndieKobbieTech Solutions (AKT) and contributors\\\\n# For license information, please see license.txt\\\\nimport frappe\\\\nfrom frappe.model.document import Document\\\\n\\\\n\\\\nclass FGPost(Document):\\\\n\\\\tdef before_insert(self):\\\\n\\\\t\\\\tspace = frappe.get_doc(\\\\\\\"FG Space\\\\\\\", self.space)\\\\n\\\\t\\\\tif space.requires_approval_to_post and not self.has_permission(\\\\\\\"write\\\\\\\"):\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t\\\\tself.is_approved = 0\\\\n\\\\n\\\\tdef on_trash(self):\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t# Cascade-delete comments so the feed doesn't show orphaned replies.\\\\n\\\\t\\\\tfrappe.db.delete(\\\\\\\"FG Comment\\\\\\\", {\\\\\\\"post\\\\\\\": self.name})\\\\n\\\", \\\"filename\\\": \\\"/home/claude/work/firstgens_community/fg_community/fg_community/doctype/fg_post/fg_post.py\\\"}\"\n\n  Line 5464:             \"file_text\": \"Feature: Posts and Comments\\n  As a FirstGens member\\n  I want to post, reply, and react inside a Space\\n  So the community feels like a real discussion forum, not a static announcement board\\n\\n  Scenario: A member creates a post in an open Space\\n    Given a Space \\\"First Year Support\\\" has requires_approval_to_post = false\\n    When I submit a post with body \\\"Anyone else nervous about freshers week?\\\"\\n    Then a new FG Post should be created with is_approved = true\\n    And it should appear at the top of the \\\"First Year Support\\\" feed\\n\\n  Scenario: A member replies to a post\\n    Given a published FG Post \\\"P-001\\\" exists in \\\"First Year Support\\\"\\n    When I submit a comment \\\"You've got this, year 1 is the hardest part\\\" on \\\"P-001\\\"\\n    Then a new FG Comment should be created linked to post \\\"P-001\\\"\\n    And the comment_count on \\\"P-001\\\" should increase by 1\\n\\n  Scenario: A comment can reply to another comment (threading)\\n    Given a FG Comment \\\"C-001\\\" exists on post \\\"P-001\\\"\\n    When I submit a comment \\\"Same here!\\\" with parent_comment \\\"C-001\\\"\\n    Then the new FG Comment should be linked with parent_comment = \\\"C-001\\\"\\n    And it should render nested under \\\"C-001\\\" in the UI, not flat in the thread\\n\\n  Scenario: Deleting a post cascades to its comments\\n    Given a FG Post \\\"P-002\\\" has 3 FG Comment records linked to it\\n    When a Space Admin deletes \\\"P-002\\\"\\n    Then all 3 linked FG Comment records should also be deleted\\n    # Implemented in fg_post.py FGPost.on_trash() — see source.\\n\\n  Scenario Outline: Post types are visually distinguishable\\n    Given I create a post with post_type \\\"<type>\\\"\\n    Then the feed should render it with the matching visual treatment\\n    Examples:\\n      | type               |\\n      | Discussion          |\\n      | Question            |\\n      | Announcement         |\\n      | Win / Celebration    |\\n\",\n\n  Line 5471:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"language\\\": \\\"plaintext\\\", \\\"code\\\": \\\"Feature: Posts and Comments\\\\n  As a FirstGens member\\\\n  I want to post, reply, and react inside a Space\\\\n  So the community feels like a real discussion forum, not a static announcement board\\\\n\\\\n  Scenario: A member creates a post in an open Space\\\\n    Given a Space \\\\\\\"First Year Support\\\\\\\" has requires_approval_to_post = false\\\\n    When I submit a post with body \\\\\\\"Anyone else nervous about freshers week?\\\\\\\"\\\\n    Then a new FG Post should be created with is_approved = true\\\\n    And it should appear at the top of the \\\\\\\"First Year Support\\\\\\\" feed\\\\n\\\\n  Scenario: A member replies to a post\\\\n    Given a published FG Post \\\\\\\"P-001\\\\\\\" exists in \\\\\\\"First Year Support\\\\\\\"\\\\n    When I submit a comment \\\\\\\"You've got this, year 1 is the hardest part\\\\\\\" on \\\\\\\"P-001\\\\\\\"\\\\n    Then a new FG Comment should be created linked to post \\\\\\\"P-001\\\\\\\"\\\\n    And the comment_count on \\\\\\\"P-001\\\\\\\" should increase by 1\\\\n\\\\n  Scenario: A comment can reply to another comment (threading)\\\\n    Given a FG Comment \\\\\\\"C-001\\\\\\\" exists on post \\\\\\\"P-001\\\\\\\"\\\\n    When I submit a comment \\\\\\\"Same here!\\\\\\\" with parent_comment \\\\\\\"C-001\\\\\\\"\\\\n    Then the new FG Comment should be linked with parent_comment = \\\\\\\"C-001\\\\\\\"\\\\n    And it should render nested under \\\\\\\"C-001\\\\\\\" in the UI, not flat in the thread\\\\n\\\\n  Scenario: Deleting a post cascades to its comments\\\\n    Given a FG Post \\\\\\\"P-002\\\\\\\" has 3 FG Comment records linked to it\\\\n    When a Space Admin deletes \\\\\\\"P-002\\\\\\\"\\\\n    Then all 3 linked FG Comment records should also be deleted\\\\n    # Implemented in fg_post.py FGPost.on_trash() \\\\u2014 see source.\\\\n\\\\n  Scenario Outline: Post types are visually distinguishable\\\\n    Given I create a post with post_type \\\\\\\"<type>\\\\\\\"\\\\n    Then the feed should render it with the matching visual treatment\\\\n    Examples:\\\\n      | type               |\\\\n      | Discussion          |\\\\n      | Quest...\n  Line 5620:             \"file_text\": \"Feature: AI Extension Points (off by default)\\n  As FirstGens' technical lead\\n  I want the AI features (sentiment classification, vector search) to be inert\\n  until deliberately switched on\\n  So the platform never silently depends on an AI model that isn't actually\\n  deployed, and so turning AI features on later is a settings change,\\n  not a database migration\\n\\n  Background:\\n    Given the \\\"FG AI Settings\\\" singleton exists with all AI features disabled\\n\\n  Scenario: A new post is created with sentiment fields blank\\n    When a member creates a FG Post\\n    Then sentiment_label should be empty\\n    And sentiment_score should be empty\\n    And no background job should be enqueued\\n    # Verifies fg_ai/sentiment.py's no-op guard (enable_sentiment check)\\n\\n  Scenario: Enabling sentiment classification requires a model path, not just a checkbox\\n    Given enable_sentiment is set to true\\n    And sentiment_onnx_model_path is left blank\\n    When a member creates a FG Post\\n    Then no classification job should run\\n    # Deliberate double-gate: ticking the box alone does nothing, by design,\\n    # to prevent half-configured AI features from silently failing in prod.\\n\\n  Scenario: A \\\"Needs Attention\\\" classification notifies the right people, not everyone\\n    Given enable_sentiment is true with a valid model path\\n    And sentiment_alert_threshold is 0.75\\n    When a post is classified as \\\"Needs Attention\\\" with score 0.82\\n    Then only the Space Admins of that specific Space should be notified\\n    And the notification should explicitly say \\\"not a diagnosis\\\"\\n    # This directly encodes the constraint from earlier in this audit: no\\n    # AI system should present a wellbeing inference as a clinical judgment.\\n    # A human Space Admin reads the actual post before doing anything.\\n\\n  Scenario: Vector search defaults to the zero-infrastructure JSON backend\\n    Given vector_store_backend is \\\"JSON column (small scale, no extra in...\n  Line 5627:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"language\\\": \\\"plaintext\\\", \\\"code\\\": \\\"Feature: AI Extension Points (off by default)\\\\n  As FirstGens' technical lead\\\\n  I want the AI features (sentiment classification, vector search) to be inert\\\\n  until deliberately switched on\\\\n  So the platform never silently depends on an AI model that isn't actually\\\\n  deployed, and so turning AI features on later is a settings change,\\\\n  not a database migration\\\\n\\\\n  Background:\\\\n    Given the \\\\\\\"FG AI Settings\\\\\\\" singleton exists with all AI features disabled\\\\n\\\\n  Scenario: A new post is created with sentiment fields blank\\\\n    When a member creates a FG Post\\\\n    Then sentiment_label should be empty\\\\n    And sentiment_score should be empty\\\\n    And no background job should be enqueued\\\\n    # Verifies fg_ai/sentiment.py's no-op guard (enable_sentiment check)\\\\n\\\\n  Scenario: Enabling sentiment classification requires a model path, not just a checkbox\\\\n    Given enable_sentiment is set to true\\\\n    And sentiment_onnx_model_path is left blank\\\\n    When a member creates a FG Post\\\\n    Then no classification job should run\\\\n    # Deliberate double-gate: ticking the box alone does nothing, by design,\\\\n    # to prevent half-configured AI features from silently failing in prod.\\\\n\\\\n  Scenario: A \\\\\\\"Needs Attention\\\\\\\" classification notifies the right people, not everyone\\\\n    Given enable_sentiment is true with a valid model path\\\\n    And sentiment_alert_threshold is 0.75\\\\n    When a post is classified as \\\\\\\"Needs Attention\\\\\\\" with score 0.82\\\\n    Then only the Space Admins of that specific Space should be notified\\\\n    And the notification should explicitly say \\\\\\\"not a diagnosis\\\\\\\"\\\\n    # This directly encodes the constraint from earlier in this audit: no\\\\n    # AI system should present a wellbeing inference as a clinical judgment.\\\\n    # A human Space Admin reads the actual post before doing anything.\\\\n\\\\n  Scenario: Vector search defaults to the zero-infrast...\n  Line 6109:             \"file_text\": \"# FirstGens Community Platform — Real Frappe App Boilerplate\\n\\n## Why this exists instead of a Lovable build\\n\\nLovable generates **React + TypeScript on Supabase**. The real Frappe UI kit (`frappe-ui`) is a **Vue 3** component library — confirmed directly against the live `frappe/lms` repo's `package.json` (`\\\"vue\\\": \\\"^3.5.27\\\"`, `\\\"frappe-ui\\\": \\\"^1.0.0-beta.7\\\"`, `\\\"pinia\\\"`, `\\\"vue-router\\\"` — no React anywhere). React and Vue can't share a render tree, so there is no partial or hybrid way to get Lovable to output real `frappe-ui` components. This isn't a Lovable limitation worth working around — it's two different JavaScript framework runtimes, full stop. Everything below is therefore real, hand-written Frappe app code: Python DocTypes on the backend, genuine `frappe-ui`/Vue 3 components on the frontend, deployable the same way any Frappe app is deployed.\\n\\nIf you still want something Lovable *can* genuinely help with: a standalone marketing/landing page for FirstGens (not part of the logged-in app, no shared components, just a public page that links to `/fg` and `/lms`) is a legitimate, non-conflicting use of it — say the word and I'll build that separately.\\n\\n## What's real upstream vs. what's custom here\\n\\n| Layer | Source | Status |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Courses, batches, certificates, quizzes, mentor-mapping | `frappe/lms` (github.com/frappe/lms, AGPL-3.0) | **Unmodified upstream dependency** — install via `bench get-app`, never forked |\\n| Discussion spaces, posts, comments, threading | `fg_community` (this app) | Custom — Circle.io doesn't exist as an open-source Frappe app, so this is genuinely new |\\n| Events (RSVP, BigBlueButton integration) | `fg_community` | Custom |\\n| Mentorship (community-wide, cross-referencing LMS course mentorship) | `fg_community` | Custom, deliberately linked to `LMS Course Mentor Mapping` rather than duplicating it |\\n| Member profiles, badges | `fg_community` (profile) + `frappe/lms` (`LMS Badge`...\n  Line 6116:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"language\\\": \\\"markdown\\\", \\\"code\\\": \\\"# FirstGens Community Platform \\\\u2014 Real Frappe App Boilerplate\\\\n\\\\n## Why this exists instead of a Lovable build\\\\n\\\\nLovable generates **React + TypeScript on Supabase**. The real Frappe UI kit (`frappe-ui`) is a **Vue 3** component library \\\\u2014 confirmed directly against the live `frappe/lms` repo's `package.json` (`\\\\\\\"vue\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"^3.5.27\\\\\\\"`, `\\\\\\\"frappe-ui\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"^1.0.0-beta.7\\\\\\\"`, `\\\\\\\"pinia\\\\\\\"`, `\\\\\\\"vue-router\\\\\\\"` \\\\u2014 no React anywhere). React and Vue can't share a render tree, so there is no partial or hybrid way to get Lovable to output real `frappe-ui` components. This isn't a Lovable limitation worth working around \\\\u2014 it's two different JavaScript framework runtimes, full stop. Everything below is therefore real, hand-written Frappe app code: Python DocTypes on the backend, genuine `frappe-ui`/Vue 3 components on the frontend, deployable the same way any Frappe app is deployed.\\\\n\\\\nIf you still want something Lovable *can* genuinely help with: a standalone marketing/landing page for FirstGens (not part of the logged-in app, no shared components, just a public page that links to `/fg` and `/lms`) is a legitimate, non-conflicting use of it \\\\u2014 say the word and I'll build that separately.\\\\n\\\\n## What's real upstream vs. what's custom here\\\\n\\\\n| Layer | Source | Status |\\\\n|---|---|---|\\\\n| Courses, batches, certificates, quizzes, mentor-mapping | `frappe/lms` (github.com/frappe/lms, AGPL-3.0) | **Unmodified upstream dependency** \\\\u2014 install via `bench get-app`, never forked |\\\\n| Discussion spaces, posts, comments, threading | `fg_community` (this app) | Custom \\\\u2014 Circle.io doesn't exist as an open-source Frappe app, so this is genuinely new |\\\\n| Events (RSVP, BigBlueButton integration) | `fg_community` | Custom |\\\\n| Mentorship (community-wide, cross-referencing LMS course mentorship) | `fg_community` | Custom, deliberately linked to `LMS Course Men...\n  Line 6555:               \"text\": \"{\\\"returncode\\\":0,\\\"stdout\\\":\\\"=== gp_project.json (the actual 'Space' doctype) fields ===\\\\n - title | Data | Title | \\\\n - description | Text Editor | Description | \\\\n - team | Link | Team | GP Team\\\\n - members | Table | Members | GP Member\\\\n - column_break_2 | Column Break | None | \\\\n - section_break_5 | Section Break | None | \\\\n - icon | Data | Icon | \\\\n - readme | Text Editor | Readme | \\\\n - section_break_14 | Section Break | None | \\\\n - tasks_count | Int | Tasks Count | \\\\n - discussions_count | Int | Discussions Count | \\\\n - archived_at | Datetime | Archived At | \\\\n - archived_by | Link | Archived By | User\\\\n - is_private | Check | Is Private | \\\\n - is_followed | Check | Is Followed | \\\\n\\\\n=== gp_guest_access.json fields ===\\\\n - user | Link | User | User\\\\n - project | Link | Project | GP Project\\\\n - team | Link | Team | GP Team\\\\n\\\\n=== gp_member.json fields ===\\\\n - user | Link | User | User\\\\n\\\",\\\"stderr\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\n\n  Line 6566:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"returncode\\\":0,\\\"stdout\\\":\\\"=== gp_project.json (the actual 'Space' doctype) fields ===\\\\n - title | Data | Title | \\\\n - description | Text Editor | Description | \\\\n - team | Link | Team | GP Team\\\\n - members | Table | Members | GP Member\\\\n - column_break_2 | Column Break | None | \\\\n - section_break_5 | Section Break | None | \\\\n - icon | Data | Icon | \\\\n - readme | Text Editor | Readme | \\\\n - section_break_14 | Section Break | None | \\\\n - tasks_count | Int | Tasks Count | \\\\n - discussions_count | Int | Discussions Count | \\\\n - archived_at | Datetime | Archived At | \\\\n - archived_by | Link | Archived By | User\\\\n - is_private | Check | Is Private | \\\\n - is_followed | Check | Is Followed | \\\\n\\\\n=== gp_guest_access.json fields ===\\\\n - user | Link | User | User\\\\n - project | Link | Project | GP Project\\\\n - team | Link | Team | GP Team\\\\n\\\\n=== gp_member.json fields ===\\\\n - user | Link | User | User\\\\n\\\",\\\"stderr\\\":\\\"\\\"}\"\n\n  Line 6595:           \"text\": \"Real finding, and it changes the recommendation: **yes, `frappe/gameplan`** (github.com/frappe/gameplan) — official `frappe` org repo, \\\"Open Source Discussions Platform for Remote Teams,\\\" 492 stars, actively committed to within hours, listed on Frappe Cloud Marketplace. I cloned it and checked the actual schema rather than trusting the marketing copy.\\n\\n**What it genuinely gives you for free, already built and maintained:**\\n\\n| Gameplan DocType | Circle.io equivalent | vs. what I hand-built |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| `GP Team` → `GP Project` | Spaces | Same idea, better: nested Team→Space hierarchy |\\n| `GP Discussion` | Posts | Same |\\n| `GP Comment` | Comments | Same |\\n| `GP Reaction` | Likes | I didn't build this |\\n| `GP Poll` / `GP Poll Option` / `GP Poll Vote` | — | I didn't build this either |\\n| `GP Task`, `GP Page` | — | Bonus features I didn't have |\\n| `GP User Profile` | Member Profile | Same |\\n| `GP Guest Access`, `GP Invitation` | — | Real external-access mechanism I didn't have |\\n\\nIt's built on the exact same Vue 3 + `frappe-ui` + TailwindCSS + Frappe backend stack as `frappe/lms`, so it slots into the same architecture cleanly. This is a strictly better foundation than what I hand-rolled, and it's about as far from \\\"random third-party dependency\\\" as anything in this ecosystem gets — it's maintained by the same org that builds Frappe itself.\\n\\n**The one real gap, and it's not a UI gap — it's a trust-model gap.** I checked `GP Guest Access`'s actual fields: it's `(user, project, team)` — a named individual explicitly granted access to one project. Membership in Gameplan is fundamentally **Team-scoped** (`GP Member` links a user to a Team; Spaces/Projects live inside a Team). That's the right model for \\\"your company's internal departments collaborating\\\" — it's the wrong model, as-is, for \\\"any first-gen student at any of 30 partner universities self-registers into an open community.\\\" Making Gameplan fit FirstGens isn't a reskin...\n  Line 6609:                   \"One single 'FirstGens' GP Team, anyone with a verified .ac.uk-style email auto-joins as a Member (closest to true open community)\",\n\n  Line 6610:                   \"GP Guest Access per-project, used as-is — university partner staff get invited per cohort, students join via a lighter custom layer\",\n\n  Line 6626:               \"text\": \"{\\n  \\\"questions\\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\\"question\\\": \\\"Before I rebuild the boilerplate against Gameplan instead: how should open student registration actually work?\\\",\\n      \\\"options\\\": [\\n        \\\"One single 'FirstGens' GP Team, anyone with a verified .ac.uk-style email auto-joins as a Member (closest to true open community)\\\",\\n        \\\"GP Guest Access per-project, used as-is \\\\u2014 university partner staff get invited per cohort, students join via a lighter custom layer\\\",\\n        \\\"Don't decide now \\\\u2014 rebuild the slim companion app (Events/Mentor Match/AI hooks) first, solve registration separately\\\"\\n      ]\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}\",\n\n  Line 6676:           \"thinking\": \"The user's decided to move forward with rebuilding the slim companion app without waiting on the registration decision, so I'm refocusing on wiring the core features—Events/RSVP, Mentor Match, and the AI hooks for sentiment analysis and vector search—directly onto Gameplan's existing DocTypes instead of my custom ones. This means I can deprecate the FG Space, FG Post, FG Comment, and FG Member Profile DocTypes I'd built earlier since Gameplan's replacing that functionality.\\n\\nFor the rebuild, I'm keeping FG Event and FG Event Attendee since Gameplan doesn't have event/RSVP capabilities, and FG Mentor Match stays mostly intact. The AI settings module needs to be retargeted so the sentiment and vector search hooks fire on GP Discussion and GP Comment instead of my old FG Post and FG Comment. I'll update the hooks configuration to declare both \\\"lms\\\" and \\\"gameplan\\\" as required upstream dependencies, and optionally let FG Event link to a GP Project the way it used to link to FG Space. Since Gameplan already has its own full Vue3 frontend for spaces, discussions, and profiles, I'm reconsidering the frontend strategy.\\n\\nRather than rebuilding the feed UI, I should drastically simplify my custom frontend to only cover Events and Mentor Match pages, then link out to Gameplan's native UI for the discussion feed. I need to check Gameplan's actual route prefix and required_apps configuration first so the link-out is accurate, then strip out Feed.vue, PostCard.vue, NewPostComposer.vue, and SpaceSidebar.vue since Gameplan provides those natively. After verifying Gameplan's hooks, I'll restructure the boilerplate by removing the old FG Space, FG Post, and FG Comment doctypes.\\n\\nUpdating the doctypes now: changing the \\\"space\\\" field in fg_event.json from linking to FG Space to linking to GP Project instead, keeping fg_mentor_match.json mostly as-is since it just needs User and mentee/mentor references, and updating hooks.py to include gameplan in requ...\n  Line 6691:               \"summary\": \"Verifying schema structure for GP Discussion and Comment.\"\n\n  Line 6705:             \"description\": \"Inspect GP Discussion/Comment fields and Gameplan's hooks.py route config\"\n\n  Line 6707:           \"message\": \"Inspect GP Discussion/Comment fields and Gameplan's hooks.py route config\",\n\n  Line 6721:               \"text\": \"{\\\"returncode\\\":1,\\\"stdout\\\":\\\"=== gp_discussion.json fields ===\\\\n - project | Link | Project | GP Project\\\\n - content | Text Editor | Content | \\\\n - status | Data | Status | \\\\n - title | Data | Title | \\\\n - reactions | Table | Reactions | GP Reaction\\\\n - team | Link | Team | GP Team\\\\n - last_post_at | Datetime | Last Post At | \\\\n - comments_count | Int | Comments Count | \\\\n - last_post_by | Link | Last Post By | User\\\\n - closed_at | Datetime | Closed At | \\\\n - closed_by | Link | Closed By | User\\\\n - slug | Data | Slug | \\\\n - participants_count | Int | Participants Count | \\\\n - pinned_at | Datetime | Pinned At | \\\\n - pinned_by | Link | Pinned By | User\\\\n - last_post_type | Select | Last Post Type | \\\\nGP Comment\\\\nGP Poll\\\\n - last_post | Dynamic Link | Last Post | last_post_type\\\\n - tags | Table | Tags | GP Tag Link\\\\n - pin_scope | Select | Pin Scope | Global\\\\nSpace\\\\n\\\\n=== gp_comment.json fields ===\\\\n - content | Text Editor | Content | \\\\n - reference_doctype | Link | Reference DocType | DocType\\\\n - reference_name | Dynamic Link | Reference Name | reference_doctype\\\\n - edited_at | Datetime | Edited At | \\\\n - reactions | Table | Reactions | GP Reaction\\\\n - deleted_at | Datetime | Deleted At | \\\\n - tags | Table | Tags | GP Tag Link\\\\n\\\\n=== hooks.py: app_name, route rules ===\\\\n\\\",\\\"stderr\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\n\n  Line 6732:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"language\\\": \\\"plaintext\\\", \\\"code\\\": \\\"=== gp_discussion.json fields ===\\\\n - project | Link | Project | GP Project\\\\n - content | Text Editor | Content | \\\\n - status | Data | Status | \\\\n - title | Data | Title | \\\\n - reactions | Table | Reactions | GP Reaction\\\\n - team | Link | Team | GP Team\\\\n - last_post_at | Datetime | Last Post At | \\\\n - comments_count | Int | Comments Count | \\\\n - last_post_by | Link | Last Post By | User\\\\n - closed_at | Datetime | Closed At | \\\\n - closed_by | Link | Closed By | User\\\\n - slug | Data | Slug | \\\\n - participants_count | Int | Participants Count | \\\\n - pinned_at | Datetime | Pinned At | \\\\n - pinned_by | Link | Pinned By | User\\\\n - last_post_type | Select | Last Post Type | \\\\nGP Comment\\\\nGP Poll\\\\n - last_post | Dynamic Link | Last Post | last_post_type\\\\n - tags | Table | Tags | GP Tag Link\\\\n - pin_scope | Select | Pin Scope | Global\\\\nSpace\\\\n\\\\n=== gp_comment.json fields ===\\\\n - content | Text Editor | Content | \\\\n - reference_doctype | Link | Reference DocType | DocType\\\\n - reference_name | Dynamic Link | Reference Name | reference_doctype\\\\n - edited_at | Datetime | Edited At | \\\\n - reactions | Table | Reactions | GP Reaction\\\\n - deleted_at | Datetime | Deleted At | \\\\n - tags | Table | Tags | GP Tag Link\\\\n\\\\n=== hooks.py: app_name, route rules ===\\\\n\\\"}\"\n\n  Line 6739:           \"thinking\": \"I'm looking at the actual schema structure now. GP Discussion has fields like project, content using a text editor rather than body, title, team, status, and slug. GP Comment uses a text editor for content but connects through a polymorphic reference system with reference_doctype and reference_name instead of a direct link field—this means comments can attach to discussions or other document types generically.\\n\\nFor my AI hook to work with comments, I need to check if reference_doctype equals \\\"GP Discussion\\\" to trace back to the parent discussion and find its project, since comments don't have a direct project field themselves. Let me look at the hooks.py file to see what's already implemented there.\",\n\n  Line 6772:               \"text\": \"{\\\"returncode\\\":0,\\\"stdout\\\":\\\"./gameplan/hooks.py\\\\n---\\\\napp_name = \\\\\\\"gameplan\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_title = \\\\\\\"Gameplan\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_publisher = \\\\\\\"Frappe Technologies Pvt Ltd\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_description = \\\\\\\"Team discussion and collaboration tool\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_email = \\\\\\\"faris@frappe.io\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_license = \\\\\\\"AGPLv3\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_icon_url = \\\\\\\"/assets/gameplan/manifest/favicon-180.png\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_icon_title = \\\\\\\"Gameplan\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_icon_route = \\\\\\\"/g\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\nadd_to_apps_screen = [\\\\n\\\\t{\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t\\\\\\\"name\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"gameplan\\\\\\\",\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t\\\\\\\"logo\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"/assets/gameplan/manifest/favicon-196.png\\\\\\\",\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t\\\\\\\"title\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"Gameplan\\\\\\\",\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t\\\\\\\"route\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"/g\\\\\\\",\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t\\\\\\\"has_permission\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"gameplan.api.can_access_gameplan\\\\\\\",\\\\n\\\\t}\\\\n]\\\\n\\\\n# Includes in <head>\\\\n# ------------------\\\\n\\\\n# include js, css files in header of desk.html\\\\n# app_include_css = \\\\\\\"/assets/gameplan/css/gameplan.css\\\\\\\"\\\\n# app_include_js = \\\\\\\"/assets/gameplan/js/gameplan.js\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\n# include js, css files in header of web template\\\\n# web_include_css = \\\\\\\"/assets/gameplan/css/gameplan.css\\\\\\\"\\\\n# web_include_js = \\\\\\\"/assets/gameplan/js/gameplan.js\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\n# include custom scss in every website theme (without file extension \\\\\\\".scss\\\\\\\")\\\\n# website_theme_scss = \\\\\\\"gameplan/public/scss/website\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\n# include js, css files in header of web form\\\\n# webform_include_js = {\\\\\\\"doctype\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"public/js/doctype.js\\\\\\\"}\\\\n# webform_include_css = {\\\\\\\"doctype\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"public/css/doctype.css\\\\\\\"}\\\\n\\\\n# include js in page\\\\n# page_js = {\\\\\\\"page\\\\\\\" : \\\\\\\"public/js/file.js\\\\\\\"}\\\\n\\\",\\\"stderr\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\n\n  Line 6783:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"returncode\\\":0,\\\"stdout\\\":\\\"./gameplan/hooks.py\\\\n---\\\\napp_name = \\\\\\\"gameplan\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_title = \\\\\\\"Gameplan\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_publisher = \\\\\\\"Frappe Technologies Pvt Ltd\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_description = \\\\\\\"Team discussion and collaboration tool\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_email = \\\\\\\"faris@frappe.io\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_license = \\\\\\\"AGPLv3\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_icon_url = \\\\\\\"/assets/gameplan/manifest/favicon-180.png\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_icon_title = \\\\\\\"Gameplan\\\\\\\"\\\\napp_icon_route = \\\\\\\"/g\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\nadd_to_apps_screen = [\\\\n\\\\t{\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t\\\\\\\"name\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"gameplan\\\\\\\",\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t\\\\\\\"logo\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"/assets/gameplan/manifest/favicon-196.png\\\\\\\",\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t\\\\\\\"title\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"Gameplan\\\\\\\",\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t\\\\\\\"route\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"/g\\\\\\\",\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t\\\\\\\"has_permission\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"gameplan.api.can_access_gameplan\\\\\\\",\\\\n\\\\t}\\\\n]\\\\n\\\\n# Includes in <head>\\\\n# ------------------\\\\n\\\\n# include js, css files in header of desk.html\\\\n# app_include_css = \\\\\\\"/assets/gameplan/css/gameplan.css\\\\\\\"\\\\n# app_include_js = \\\\\\\"/assets/gameplan/js/gameplan.js\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\n# include js, css files in header of web template\\\\n# web_include_css = \\\\\\\"/assets/gameplan/css/gameplan.css\\\\\\\"\\\\n# web_include_js = \\\\\\\"/assets/gameplan/js/gameplan.js\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\n# include custom scss in every website theme (without file extension \\\\\\\".scss\\\\\\\")\\\\n# website_theme_scss = \\\\\\\"gameplan/public/scss/website\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\n# include js, css files in header of web form\\\\n# webform_include_js = {\\\\\\\"doctype\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"public/js/doctype.js\\\\\\\"}\\\\n# webform_include_css = {\\\\\\\"doctype\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"public/css/doctype.css\\\\\\\"}\\\\n\\\\n# include js in page\\\\n# page_js = {\\\\\\\"page\\\\\\\" : \\\\\\\"public/js/file.js\\\\\\\"}\\\\n\\\",\\\"stderr\\\":\\\"\\\"}\"\n\n  Line 6790:           \"thinking\": \"I've confirmed the app details—gameplan with route /g and AGPLv3 license from Frappe Technologies. Now I'm planning the rebuild: I need to delete the FG-specific doctype folders, update the fg_event.json to reference GP Project instead of FG Space, and keep fg_mentor_match.json since it doesn't depend on the space field.\\n\\nFor the sentiment analysis logic, I'm reworking the classify_on_create function to handle the different ways discussions and comments reference their parent project—GP Discussion has it directly while GP Comment needs to traverse through the reference. I'm also updating the notification system to target GP Project members instead of space admins, though I need to figure out the right notification recipients since GP Project doesn't have an explicit admin role, just team members and the project owner.\\n\\nFor vector search, I'm updating the embedding logic to work with GP Discussion and optionally GP Comment, making sure to use the correct field names like \\\"content\\\" for discussions instead of \\\"body\\\". Finally, I need to update hooks.py to add the new required app dependency for Gameplan and set up the doc_events for both discussion and comment types with the new embedding and sentiment fields.\",\n\n  Line 7101:           \"thinking\": \"I've got the tools I need for messaging, and I'll have the agent create markdown documentation files directly in a /docs folder rather than relying on the project knowledge field. Now I'm calling create_project with a detailed prompt and initial message, keeping in mind that this could take a while since the schema and UI generation might run up to the full timeout window.\\n\\nI'm drafting the initial message now—I want to be specific enough about the schema and types to ensure fidelity to the real Frappe DocTypes, but written in natural language that the Lovable agent can work with effectively. The key constraint is that this is a visual prototype for stakeholders to interact with, even though the production system will eventually be built on Frappe Framework using their open-source LMS and Gameplan apps.\\n\\nNow I'm laying out the Supabase schema to mirror the Frappe DocTypes field-for-field wherever it makes sense, so the eventual port is just a translation exercise rather than a redesign. I'm including the core tables from frappe/gameplan like teams, projects (called \\\"Spaces\\\" in the UI), discussions (shown as \\\"Posts\\\"), comments, reactions, and user profiles. For the LMS side, I'm keeping it intentionally minimal—just a read-only stub that links out visually, since the real learning management system will live elsewhere.\\n\\nBeyond that, I'm adding custom tables for events and event attendees that don't exist upstream, matching the structure of a custom Frappe app. Events have flexible location types (online via BigBlueButton, external links, or in-person), RSVP tracking, and capacity limits, while attendees track who's coming and their response status.\\n\\nI'm also setting up mentor matching to track mentee-mentor pairs with their status and how they were matched, plus a single settings row to control two AI features — sentiment analysis and vector search — both of which will be mocked and clearly labeled as such rather than calling real M...\n  Line 7130:             \"prompt\": \"Build \\\"FirstGens Community\\\" — a React/TypeScript/Supabase clickable UX prototype for a community platform supporting first-generation university students. This is EXPLICITLY a visual/UX prototype for stakeholders to click through, not the production system — the real production system will be built later on Frappe Framework using the open-source frappe/lms and frappe/gameplan apps. The single most important constraint: structure the Supabase schema and TypeScript types to mirror the real Frappe DocTypes field-for-field wherever reasonable, so porting later is a translation exercise, not a redesign.\\n\\nSUPABASE SCHEMA (mirror these real Frappe DocTypes by name and fields):\\n\\nFrom frappe/gameplan (an existing open-source Frappe app for team discussions — do not invent different field names):\\n- gp_team: id, title\\n- gp_project (shown in UI as \\\"Spaces\\\"): id, title, description, team_id (fk gp_team), icon, is_private (bool), discussions_count, tasks_count\\n- gp_discussion (shown in UI as \\\"Posts\\\"): id, project_id (fk gp_project), team_id, title, content (rich text), status, pinned_at, pinned_by, comments_count, participants_count, last_post_at\\n- gp_comment: id, content (rich text), reference_doctype ('gp_discussion'), reference_name (fk), edited_at, deleted_at\\n- gp_reaction: id, reference_doctype, reference_name, user_id, emoji\\n- gp_user_profile: user_id, bio, cover_image, profile_image\\n\\nFrom frappe/lms (DO NOT reimplement courses/lessons/quizzes — just a thin read-only \\\"Courses\\\" stub page that visually links out, since this is intentionally NOT where the LMS lives in the real architecture):\\n- courses (mock only): id, title, short_introduction, image — just enough for a simple card grid. Label clearly in the UI: \\\"Real implementation lives in frappe/lms, not duplicated here.\\\"\\n\\nCustom tables (these don't exist upstream — genuinely new, will become a small custom Frappe app called \\\"fg_companion\\\"):\\n- fg_event: id, title, descripti...\n  Line 7146:               \"text\": \"{\\n  \\\"$schema\\\": \\\"https://api.lovable.dev/V1CreateProjectResponse.json\\\",\\n  \\\"id\\\": \\\"d07c1ea6-a6f9-44ba-aad3-ad94dd714078\\\",\\n  \\\"workspace_id\\\": \\\"oWhZBzSEWehAFsADuLwp\\\",\\n  \\\"description\\\": \\\"Build \\\\\\\"FirstGens Community\\\\\\\" — a React/TypeScript/Supabase clickable UX prototype for a community platform supporting first-generation university students. This is EXPLICITLY a visual/UX prototype for stakeholders to click through, not the production system — the real production system will be built later on Frappe Framework using the open-source frappe/lms and frappe/gameplan apps. The single most important constraint: structure the Supabase schema and TypeScript types to mirror the real Frappe DocTypes field-for-field wherever reasonable, so porting later is a translation exercise, not a redesign.\\\\n\\\\nSUPABASE SCHEMA (mirror these real Frappe DocTypes by name and fields):\\\\n\\\\nFrom frappe/gameplan (an existing open-source Frappe app for team discussions — do not invent different field names):\\\\n- gp_team: id, title\\\\n- gp_project (shown in UI as \\\\\\\"Spaces\\\\\\\"): id, title, description, team_id (fk gp_team), icon, is_private (bool), discussions_count, tasks_count\\\\n- gp_discussion (shown in UI as \\\\\\\"Posts\\\\\\\"): id, project_id (fk gp_project), team_id, title, content (rich text), status, pinned_at, pinned_by, comments_count, participants_count, last_post_at\\\\n- gp_comment: id, content (rich text), reference_doctype ('gp_discussion'), reference_name (fk), edited_at, deleted_at\\\\n- gp_reaction: id, reference_doctype, reference_name, user_id, emoji\\\\n- gp_user_profile: user_id, bio, cover_image, profile_image\\\\n\\\\nFrom frappe/lms (DO NOT reimplement courses/lessons/quizzes — just a thin read-only \\\\\\\"Courses\\\\\\\" stub page that visually links out, since this is intentionally NOT where the LMS lives in the real architecture):\\\\n- courses (mock only): id, title, short_introduction, image — just enough for a simple card grid. Label clearly in the UI...\n  Line 7160:             \"description\": \"Build \\\"FirstGens Community\\\" — a React/TypeScript/Supabase clickable UX prototype for a community platform supporting first-generation university students. This is EXPLICITLY a visual/UX prototype for stakeholders to click through, not the production system — the real production system will be built later on Frappe Framework using the open-source frappe/lms and frappe/gameplan apps. The single most important constraint: structure the Supabase schema and TypeScript types to mirror the real Frappe DocTypes field-for-field wherever reasonable, so porting later is a translation exercise, not a redesign.\\n\\nSUPABASE SCHEMA (mirror these real Frappe DocTypes by name and fields):\\n\\nFrom frappe/gameplan (an existing open-source Frappe app for team discussions — do not invent different field names):\\n- gp_team: id, title\\n- gp_project (shown in UI as \\\"Spaces\\\"): id, title, description, team_id (fk gp_team), icon, is_private (bool), discussions_count, tasks_count\\n- gp_discussion (shown in UI as \\\"Posts\\\"): id, project_id (fk gp_project), team_id, title, content (rich text), status, pinned_at, pinned_by, comments_count, participants_count, last_post_at\\n- gp_comment: id, content (rich text), reference_doctype ('gp_discussion'), reference_name (fk), edited_at, deleted_at\\n- gp_reaction: id, reference_doctype, reference_name, user_id, emoji\\n- gp_user_profile: user_id, bio, cover_image, profile_image\\n\\nFrom frappe/lms (DO NOT reimplement courses/lessons/quizzes — just a thin read-only \\\"Courses\\\" stub page that visually links out, since this is intentionally NOT where the LMS lives in the real architecture):\\n- courses (mock only): id, title, short_introduction, image — just enough for a simple card grid. Label clearly in the UI: \\\"Real implementation lives in frappe/lms, not duplicated here.\\\"\\n\\nCustom tables (these don't exist upstream — genuinely new, will become a small custom Frappe app called \\\"fg_companion\\\"):\\n- fg_event: id, title, desc...\n  Line 7181:             \"json_block\": \"{\\n  \\\"$schema\\\": \\\"https://api.lovable.dev/V1CreateProjectResponse.json\\\",\\n  \\\"id\\\": \\\"d07c1ea6-a6f9-44ba-aad3-ad94dd714078\\\",\\n  \\\"workspace_id\\\": \\\"oWhZBzSEWehAFsADuLwp\\\",\\n  \\\"description\\\": \\\"Build \\\\\\\"FirstGens Community\\\\\\\" — a React/TypeScript/Supabase clickable UX prototype for a community platform supporting first-generation university students. This is EXPLICITLY a visual/UX prototype for stakeholders to click through, not the production system — the real production system will be built later on Frappe Framework using the open-source frappe/lms and frappe/gameplan apps. The single most important constraint: structure the Supabase schema and TypeScript types to mirror the real Frappe DocTypes field-for-field wherever reasonable, so porting later is a translation exercise, not a redesign.\\\\n\\\\nSUPABASE SCHEMA (mirror these real Frappe DocTypes by name and fields):\\\\n\\\\nFrom frappe/gameplan (an existing open-source Frappe app for team discussions — do not invent different field names):\\\\n- gp_team: id, title\\\\n- gp_project (shown in UI as \\\\\\\"Spaces\\\\\\\"): id, title, description, team_id (fk gp_team), icon, is_private (bool), discussions_count, tasks_count\\\\n- gp_discussion (shown in UI as \\\\\\\"Posts\\\\\\\"): id, project_id (fk gp_project), team_id, title, content (rich text), status, pinned_at, pinned_by, comments_count, participants_count, last_post_at\\\\n- gp_comment: id, content (rich text), reference_doctype ('gp_discussion'), reference_name (fk), edited_at, deleted_at\\\\n- gp_reaction: id, reference_doctype, reference_name, user_id, emoji\\\\n- gp_user_profile: user_id, bio, cover_image, profile_image\\\\n\\\\nFrom frappe/lms (DO NOT reimplement courses/lessons/quizzes — just a thin read-only \\\\\\\"Courses\\\\\\\" stub page that visually links out, since this is intentionally NOT where the LMS lives in the real architecture):\\\\n- courses (mock only): id, title, short_introduction, image — just enough for a simple card grid. Label clearly in th...\n  Line 7215:             \"message\": \"Understood — Lovable Cloud is disabled, so skip Supabase entirely for now. Build the exact same \\\"FirstGens Community\\\" prototype (same schema/types, same pages, same mocked AI features, same /docs markdown files) but using in-memory TypeScript mock data (plain arrays/objects in a /src/mock-data folder, typed to match the schema I described) instead of any database. No Supabase client, no Lovable Cloud calls anywhere.\\n\\nKeep the TypeScript types named and shaped exactly as specified (GPTeam, GPProject, GPDiscussion, GPComment, GPReaction, GPUserProfile, FGEvent, FGEventAttendee, FGMentorMatch, FGAISettings) so that when Lovable Cloud is enabled later, swapping the mock-data layer for real Supabase tables is a contained, mechanical change rather than a rewrite — note this explicitly in /docs/01_SCHEMA_MAPPING_TO_FRAPPE.md as \\\"currently in-memory mock data; same shape will become Supabase tables once Lovable Cloud is enabled, which will then map 1:1 to the real Frappe DocTypes as already documented.\\\"\\n\\nPlease build the full thing now: sidebar, home feed, space pages, post detail with comments + mocked similar-posts, events with RSVP (in-memory), mentor match page, member profiles, the courses stub, and all 4 /docs markdown files. Seed the mock data with the same realistic demo content (First Year Support and Mentor Lounge spaces, several posts/comments, a couple of events, a couple of mentor matches).\",\n\n  Line 7373:             \"message\": \"Understood — Lovable Cloud is disabled, so skip Supabase entirely for now. Build the exact same \\\"FirstGens Community\\\" prototype (same schema/types, same pages, same mocked AI features, same /docs markdown files) but using in-memory TypeScript mock data (plain arrays/objects in a /src/mock-data folder, typed to match the schema I described) instead of any database. No Supabase client, no Lovable Cloud calls anywhere.\\n\\nKeep the TypeScript types named and shaped exactly as specified (GPTeam, GPProject, GPDiscussion, GPComment, GPReaction, GPUserProfile, FGEvent, FGEventAttendee, FGMentorMatch, FGAISettings) so that when Lovable Cloud is enabled later, swapping the mock-data layer for real Supabase tables is a contained, mechanical change rather than a rewrite — note this explicitly in /docs/01_SCHEMA_MAPPING_TO_FRAPPE.md as \\\"currently in-memory mock data; same shape will become Supabase tables once Lovable Cloud is enabled, which will then map 1:1 to the real Frappe DocTypes as already documented.\\\"\\n\\nPlease build the full thing now: sidebar, home feed, space pages, post detail with comments + mocked similar-posts, events with RSVP (in-memory), mentor match page, member profiles, the courses stub, and all 4 /docs markdown files. Seed the mock data with the same realistic demo content (First Year Support and Mentor Lounge spaces, several posts/comments, a couple of events, a couple of mentor matches).\",\n\n  Line 7666:           \"text\": \"Good, now I have real current data instead of guessing. Here's the full picture.\\n\\n## Work package estimate — porting to real Frappe (lms + gameplan + fg_companion)\\n\\nAssumptions stated up front: solo build, building on the DocType/Python boilerplate already produced earlier in this thread (not starting from zero), and using your own established ~5 hrs/week side-hustle capacity rather than a fantasy full-time pace.\\n\\n| WP | Scope | Effort (hrs) | Notes |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| WP1 | OCI provisioning at the corrected 2 OCPU/12GB spec, bench/MariaDB/Redis, DNS/SSL | 8–12 | Known territory given your existing AKCloud work |\\n| WP2 | Install `frappe/lms` unmodified, branding/config | 4–6 | Low risk, it's a real working app |\\n| WP3 | Install `frappe/gameplan`, resolve the **open registration/membership question** we deferred | 15–25 | **Highest-uncertainty item.** Depends entirely on which of the three options from earlier you pick — auto-join-by-email is cheap, a real self-serve onboarding flow is not |\\n| WP4 | Build `fg_companion` (Events/RSVP, Mentor Match, Custom Fields onto GP Discussion/Comment) | 12–18 | Most of the DocType/Python scaffolding already exists from this conversation |\\n| WP5 | Sentiment AI (real ONNX model, not the mock) | 10–15 | **Deferrable to v2** |\\n| WP6 | Vector search AI (EmbeddingGemma) | 8–12 | **Deferrable to v2** |\\n| WP7 | Visual/brand cohesion across 3 different apps' UIs (LMS + Gameplan + fg_companion need to feel like one product, not three) | 10–20 | Routinely underestimated — this is real design work, not config |\\n| WP8 | Testing against the 6 Gherkin spec files, bug-fixing | 10–15 | |\\n| WP9 | UAT with Alaya/stakeholders, iteration | 8–12 | Calendar-bound by her availability more than your hours |\\n| WP10 | Deployment, monitoring, handover docs | 5–8 | |\\n\\n**Totals:** MVP without AI features (WP1–4, 7–10) ≈ **72–113 hours** → at 5 hrs/week, **~14–23 weeks, roughly 3.5–5.5 months**. Full version with both AI...\n  Line 7936:           \"extracted_content\": \"## Goal\\r\\nFix the Community Launchpad prototype (Vue 3 + Vite 8 + Tailwind v4) — make all user journeys work per Gherkin scenarios, verify all Frappe ecosystem DocType mappings are correct, and ensure the app is fully functional at `http://localhost:8080`.\\r\\n\\r\\n## Constraints & Preferences\\r\\n- Production target stack: Frappe Framework + Gameplan + LMS + Raven + Helpdesk + Wiki + EPS + payments\\r\\n- App should look and behave like Circle.so (designed in Lovable, refactored to Vue 3)\\r\\n- In-memory mock store today, TypeScript types 1:1 mirror real Frappe DocType field names\\r\\n- Billing by Frappe (frappe/payments) should be integrated — \\\"it should just work\\\"\\r\\n- Backup folder required before making changes\\r\\n- Each version marked as working on it\\r\\n\\r\\n## Progress\\r\\n### Done\\r\\n- Created backup at `C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\community-launchpad-proto-backup-pre-fix`\\r\\n- Fixed missing `@tailwindcss/vite` plugin (was causing completely unstyled page)\\r\\n- Removed 46 leftover React `.tsx` files from `src/components/ui/` and `src/hooks/`\\r\\n- Cleaned `package.json`: removed `lucide-react`, renamed from `tanstack_start_ts` to `community-launchpad-proto`\\r\\n- Updated README.md: React 19/TanStack → Vue 3/Vue Router 4 throughout\\r\\n- ESLint config verified working (no React plugins, Vue plugins only)\\r\\n- Added \\\"Message\\\" button to mentor match cards (Gherkin scenario 1: DMs)\\r\\n- Added search/filter + action buttons to MembersView (Gherkin scenario 4)\\r\\n- Created `PollCard.vue` component with voting, percentages, animated bars (Gherkin scenario 7)\\r\\n- Added `FGPoll`, `FGPollVote` types + seed data + store functions\\r\\n- Added `FGBadge`, `FGBadgeAward`, energy points system (Gherkin scenario 8)\\r\\n- Added badges/achievements section to `MemberDetailView`\\r\\n- Added `createEvent()` store function + New Event modal to EventsView\\r\\n- Added all 12 doc files to DocsView index\\r\\n- Build passes: `✓ built in ~800ms`, all chunks emitted clean...\n  Line 7952:           \"thinking\": \"I'm looking at a context handoff document describing a Community Launchpad prototype that's been built locally in Vue 3 with Vite and Tailwind, running on Windows at localhost:8080—this appears to be work from a different session or local development environment, not something I'm currently working on.\\n\\nThe user is signaling that they've actually built something real and functional this time, moving past the earlier failed Lovable attempt. I should acknowledge the genuine progress here while being careful to evaluate what's actually been accomplished versus what might be aspirational or inconsistent in the documentation (like the pgvector setup despite using MariaDB).\\n\\nBut I'm noticing a major scope expansion that wasn't part of our original verification — the production stack now includes Raven, Helpdesk, Wiki, and an Energy Points System on top of the frappe/LMS and gameplan components we'd discussed. I haven't actually verified these are real, compatible apps with the claimed DocTypes and integrations, which is exactly the kind of unverified architecture claim I've been flagging throughout this conversation as a pattern to watch for.\\n\\nMore concerning, some of the \\\"Critical Context\\\" findings are making very specific field-level claims about how these apps work — like the GP Discussion reactions being stored as a child table — but this directly contradicts what I actually found when I cloned the frappe/gameplan repo earlier. I discovered gp_reaction as its own separate DocType folder with a polymorphic reference pattern, not a child table structure, so I need to reconcile whether I'm misremembering my own verification or if there's confabulation happening here.\\n\\nI should actually check the gp_reaction.json file directly since I have the repo cloned locally, and verify a few other specific claims like whether GP Comment has a title field and what the last_post_type field actually supports — these are all checkable facts I can confirm...\n  Line 7991:             \"description\": \"Re-verify the GP* claims against the real gameplan repo already cloned\"\n\n  Line 7993:           \"message\": \"Re-verify the GP* claims against the real gameplan repo already cloned\",\n\n  Line 8007:               \"text\": \"{\\\"returncode\\\":0,\\\"stdout\\\":\\\"=== gp_reaction.json — istable + full fields ===\\\\nistable: 1\\\\n - emoji | Data | \\\\n - user | Data | \\\\n\\\\n=== gp_discussion.json — FULL field list (re-check for last_post_type/last_post) ===\\\\n - project | Link | GP Project\\\\n - content | Text Editor | \\\\n - status | Data | \\\\n - title | Data | \\\\n - reactions | Table | GP Reaction\\\\n - team | Link | GP Team\\\\n - last_post_at | Datetime | \\\\n - comments_count | Int | \\\\n - last_post_by | Link | User\\\\n - closed_at | Datetime | \\\\n - closed_by | Link | User\\\\n - slug | Data | \\\\n - participants_count | Int | \\\\n - pinned_at | Datetime | \\\\n - pinned_by | Link | User\\\\n - last_post_type | Select | \\\\nGP Comment\\\\nGP Poll\\\\n - last_post | Dynamic Link | last_post_type\\\\n - tags | Table | GP Tag Link\\\\n - pin_scope | Select | Global\\\\nSpace\\\\n\\\\n=== gp_comment.json — confirm no title field ===\\\\n - content | Text Editor\\\\n - reference_doctype | Link\\\\n - reference_name | Dynamic Link\\\\n - edited_at | Datetime\\\\n - reactions | Table\\\\n - deleted_at | Datetime\\\\n - tags | Table\\\\n\\\\n=== gp_project.json — re-confirm members field exists ===\\\\n - title | Data | \\\\n - description | Text Editor | \\\\n - team | Link | GP Team\\\\n - members | Table | GP Member\\\\n - column_break_2 | Column Break | \\\\n - section_break_5 | Section Break | \\\\n - icon | Data | \\\\n - readme | Text Editor | \\\\n - section_break_14 | Section Break | \\\\n - tasks_count | Int | \\\\n - discussions_count | Int | \\\\n - archived_at | Datetime | \\\\n - archived_by | Link | User\\\\n - is_private | Check | \\\\n - is_followed | Check | \\\\n\\\",\\\"stderr\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\n\n  Line 8018:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"returncode\\\":0,\\\"stdout\\\":\\\"=== gp_reaction.json — istable + full fields ===\\\\nistable: 1\\\\n - emoji | Data | \\\\n - user | Data | \\\\n\\\\n=== gp_discussion.json — FULL field list (re-check for last_post_type/last_post) ===\\\\n - project | Link | GP Project\\\\n - content | Text Editor | \\\\n - status | Data | \\\\n - title | Data | \\\\n - reactions | Table | GP Reaction\\\\n - team | Link | GP Team\\\\n - last_post_at | Datetime | \\\\n - comments_count | Int | \\\\n - last_post_by | Link | User\\\\n - closed_at | Datetime | \\\\n - closed_by | Link | User\\\\n - slug | Data | \\\\n - participants_count | Int | \\\\n - pinned_at | Datetime | \\\\n - pinned_by | Link | User\\\\n - last_post_type | Select | \\\\nGP Comment\\\\nGP Poll\\\\n - last_post | Dynamic Link | last_post_type\\\\n - tags | Table | GP Tag Link\\\\n - pin_scope | Select | Global\\\\nSpace\\\\n\\\\n=== gp_comment.json — confirm no title field ===\\\\n - content | Text Editor\\\\n - reference_doctype | Link\\\\n - reference_name | Dynamic Link\\\\n - edited_at | Datetime\\\\n - reactions | Table\\\\n - deleted_at | Datetime\\\\n - tags | Table\\\\n\\\\n=== gp_project.json — re-confirm members field exists ===\\\\n - title | Data | \\\\n - description | Text Editor | \\\\n - team | Link | GP Team\\\\n - members | Table | GP Member\\\\n - column_break_2 | Column Break | \\\\n - section_break_5 | Section Break | \\\\n - icon | Data | \\\\n - readme | Text Editor | \\\\n - section_break_14 | Section Break | \\\\n - tasks_count | Int | \\\\n - discussions_count | Int | \\\\n - archived_at | Datetime | \\\\n - archived_by | Link | User\\\\n - is_private | Check | \\\\n - is_followed | Check | \\\\n\\\",\\\"stderr\\\":\\\"\\\"}\"\n\n  Line 8025:           \"thinking\": \"I'm verifying the critical context claims against the actual schema files. The first claim about how Frappe stores reactions as a child table rather than separate linked records checks out—the GP Reaction schema has the table flag set, and the GP Discussion schema references it as a Table field type.\\n\\nNow I'm seeing that GP Comment also has its own reactions table field, so reactions are nested at both the discussion and comment levels as child tables. This is different from what I described in my earlier Lovable prompt, where I incorrectly specified gp_reaction with reference_doctype and reference_name fields—the actual implementation is much simpler, with reactions as direct child table entries containing just emoji and user fields. That was a mistake on my part in how I framed the architecture initially.\\n\\nLooking at my other claims: the last_post_type and last_post fields on discussions are confirmed accurate, and GP Comment definitely lacks a title field like the prototype has. For the GP Project claim about being a child of GP Team, the team field link is correct, but I need to clarify whether I was describing what's wrong with the prototype versus what's actually in the real repo. Now I need to verify the LMS Course upcoming field against the actual schema, and then check the claims about Raven, Helpdesk, and EPS since I haven't examined those repositories yet.\",\n\n  Line 8044:           \"text\": \"Strong result: every GP-specific claim I could re-check against the actual repo is **accurate** — reactions genuinely are a child table (`istable: 1`) on both `GP Discussion` and `GP Comment`, not separate linked records; `last_post_type`/`last_post` genuinely exist; `GP Comment` genuinely has no `title` field. This is a meaningfully more careful piece of work than the original Gemini research. One thing worth flagging on my own account: my Lovable prompt earlier told it to build `gp_reaction` with `reference_doctype`/`reference_name` fields — that's now confirmed **wrong**; the real shape is a simple child table. Now let me check the claims I haven't touched yet — LMS's `upcoming` field, and whether Raven/Helpdesk/EPS are even real in the way described, since those are new additions to scope I never verified.\",\n\n  Line 9044:           \"text\": \"This is real, substantial progress — Tailwind v4 plugin fix, dead React file cleanup, working build, multiple Gherkin scenarios actually implemented, backups before changes. That's legitimate engineering discipline, not a vibes-only session.\\n\\nI cross-checked the \\\"Critical Context\\\" claims against the real repos — I already had `gameplan` and `lms` cloned from earlier, and pulled `raven`, `eps`, `payments`, and `frappe` core fresh just now to check the new ones. Scorecard:\\n\\n## Confirmed correct (verified directly against the actual repo source)\\n\\n| Claim | Verdict |\\n|---|---|\\n| `GP Discussion`/`GP Comment` reactions are a child table (`istable: 1`), not `reference_doctype`/`reference_name` records | **True** |\\n| `GP Discussion` has `last_post_type` (Select: GP Comment/GP Poll) + `last_post` (Dynamic Link) | **True** |\\n| `GP Comment` has no `title` field | **True** |\\n| `GP Project` → `GP Team`, with a `members` Table field the prototype hasn't mapped yet | **True** |\\n| `LMS Course` has an `upcoming` Check field | **True** |\\n| `Raven Channel` has `is_direct_message` | **True** |\\n\\n## Wrong or needs correction — these need fixing before they go further\\n\\n1. **`frappe/payments` has no `Subscription` DocType at all.** I checked every doctype in that repo — it's purely payment-gateway connector settings (Stripe, PayPal, Razorpay, GoCardless, Mpesa, Braintree). The real `Subscription` / `Subscription Plan` system with billing intervals and statuses lives in **ERPNext**, confirmed via Frappe's own docs. That's a materially heavier dependency than \\\"frappe/payments\\\" implies — ERPNext is a full accounting/ERP suite, not a thin add-on. If \\\"billing should just work\\\" is a hard requirement, the real cost is pulling in ERPNext, not just `frappe/payments` — worth knowing before that gets treated as a small ticket.\\n\\n2. **`Raven Message.message_type` exists, but the options are wrong.** Doc says `Text/JSON/HTML/Markdown`. Real options, confirmed ...\n  Line 9638:               \"text\": \"## Goal\\n\\nExtend the FirstGens prototype's `/docs` with a deep Frappe-ecosystem audit so you can see, per Circle.so feature, **what Frappe already gives us, what's missing, what we'd build, and what the resulting UX looks like in Gherkin** — then lock the decisions in as ADRs in the UK GDS December-2025 format you already use for ADR-001.\\n\\nNothing in `src/` changes. This is documentation-only so the prototype keeps working while stakeholders read the strategy.\\n\\n## What I found in the Frappe ecosystem\\n\\nThree buckets, mapped to Circle.so:\\n\\n**Already covered (use as-is):**\\n\\n- DMs / channels → **Raven** (The-Commit-Company, AGPL, production, has React Native mobile)\\n- Notifications, SSO/OAuth2, global search (new SQLite FTS5, July 2025) → **Frappe Framework core**\\n- Wiki / Knowledge Base → **frappe/wiki**\\n- Helpdesk / ticketed safeguarding reports → **frappe/helpdesk**\\n- Analytics / BI → **frappe/insights**\\n- Gamification points + leaderboards → **frappe/eps** (Energy Points, spun out April 2025)\\n- Email digests primitive → **frappe/newsletter** (official, new)\\n- Scheduled live classes → **frappe/lms** Zoom/BBB integration\\n- Video calls → **frappe/meet** (WebRTC, early, July 2025)\\n- Automation → Server Scripts + Workflows + **otto** (upcoming official AI agent platform)\\n\\n**Partial / needs glue:**\\n\\n- Paywalls → frappe/payments + ERPNext Subscriptions exist, but no Space-gating UX\\n- Email digests → engine exists, no \\\"this week in your community\\\" generator\\n- Mobile → Raven mobile covers chat only, no full community app\\n- Live events → no broadcast/webinar (1-to-many) mode (implement developer mode for msft so i can add end to end teams and any workflows with that it got to all work but leave the instruction in settings if i have to do anything external with a msft dev account or anything) id like u to start form that first and fore more before anthing else u have to do always rememer u are developing the frappe pay so if ...\n  Line 9647:             \"text\": \"## Goal\\n\\nExtend the FirstGens prototype's `/docs` with a deep Frappe-ecosystem audit so you can see, per Circle.so feature, **what Frappe already gives us, what's missing, what we'd build, and what the resulting UX looks like in Gherkin** — then lock the decisions in as ADRs in the UK GDS December-2025 format you already use for ADR-001.\\n\\nNothing in `src/` changes. This is documentation-only so the prototype keeps working while stakeholders read the strategy.\\n\\n## What I found in the Frappe ecosystem\\n\\nThree buckets, mapped to Circle.so:\\n\\n**Already covered (use as-is):**\\n\\n- DMs / channels → **Raven** (The-Commit-Company, AGPL, production, has React Native mobile)\\n- Notifications, SSO/OAuth2, global search (new SQLite FTS5, July 2025) → **Frappe Framework core**\\n- Wiki / Knowledge Base → **frappe/wiki**\\n- Helpdesk / ticketed safeguarding reports → **frappe/helpdesk**\\n- Analytics / BI → **frappe/insights**\\n- Gamification points + leaderboards → **frappe/eps** (Energy Points, spun out April 2025)\\n- Email digests primitive → **frappe/newsletter** (official, new)\\n- Scheduled live classes → **frappe/lms** Zoom/BBB integration\\n- Video calls → **frappe/meet** (WebRTC, early, July 2025)\\n- Automation → Server Scripts + Workflows + **otto** (upcoming official AI agent platform)\\n\\n**Partial / needs glue:**\\n\\n- Paywalls → frappe/payments + ERPNext Subscriptions exist, but no Space-gating UX\\n- Email digests → engine exists, no \\\"this week in your community\\\" generator\\n- Mobile → Raven mobile covers chat only, no full community app\\n- Live events → no broadcast/webinar (1-to-many) mode (implement developer mode for msft so i can add end to end teams and any workflows with that it got to all work but leave the instruction in settings if i have to do anything external with a msft dev account or anything) id like u to start form that first and fore more before anthing else u have to do always rememer u are developing the frappe pay so if th...\n  Line 9707:               \"text\": \"# 08 — Frappe Ecosystem Gap Analysis (Circle.so → Frappe)\\n\\nAudit of every Frappe-ecosystem app/module that could replace a Circle.so feature for the FirstGens Community platform. Rating: ⭐ production / 🟡 partial-or-early / 🔴 abandoned-or-missing.\\n\\n## Summary matrix\\n\\n| # | Circle feature | Best Frappe option | Repo / module | Status | Gap |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| 1 | Direct messages, channels, threads | **Raven** | github.com/The-Commit-Company/Raven | ⭐ | None — has React Native mobile |\\n| 2 | Notifications (in-app + email) | Frappe Framework core | github.com/frappe/frappe | ⭐ | Push needs FCM glue |\\n| 3 | Live events / video | **frappe/meet** (WebRTC) + LMS Zoom/BBB | github.com/frappe/meet, github.com/frappe/lms | 🟡 | No broadcast/webinar; **Teams integration is custom** (see ADR-003) |\\n| 4 | Member directory (public, filterable) | — (LMS profile is course-centric) | — | 🔴 | Build on Framework |\\n| 5 | Paywalls / membership tiers | frappe/payments + ERPNext Subscription | github.com/frappe/payments | 🟡 | No Space-gating UX |\\n| 6 | Email digests | frappe/newsletter | github.com/frappe/newsletter | 🟡 | Engine only, no \\\"this-week-in\\\" generator |\\n| 7 | Helpdesk / safeguarding tickets | **frappe/helpdesk** | github.com/frappe/helpdesk | ⭐ | None |\\n| 8 | Community moderation (word filters, AI flag, queues, appeals) | — | — | 🔴 | Build on Framework |\\n| 9 | Wiki / knowledge base | **frappe/wiki** | github.com/frappe/wiki | ⭐ | None |\\n| 10 | Polls / surveys | frappe/poll (abandoned 2016); LMS quizzes for course context | — | 🔴 | Build on Framework |\\n| 11 | Gamification / badges | **frappe/eps** (Energy Points) | github.com/frappe/eps | ⭐ | Points & leaderboards yes; visual badge UI no |\\n| 12 | Global search | Framework SQLite FTS5 (July 2025) | github.com/frappe/frappe | ⭐ | Cross-content wiring needed |\\n| 13 | Analytics / BI | **frappe/insights** | github.com/frappe/insights | ⭐ | No prebuilt community dashboards |...\n  Line 9716:             \"text\": \"# 08 — Frappe Ecosystem Gap Analysis (Circle.so → Frappe)\\n\\nAudit of every Frappe-ecosystem app/module that could replace a Circle.so feature for the FirstGens Community platform. Rating: ⭐ production / 🟡 partial-or-early / 🔴 abandoned-or-missing.\\n\\n## Summary matrix\\n\\n| # | Circle feature | Best Frappe option | Repo / module | Status | Gap |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| 1 | Direct messages, channels, threads | **Raven** | github.com/The-Commit-Company/Raven | ⭐ | None — has React Native mobile |\\n| 2 | Notifications (in-app + email) | Frappe Framework core | github.com/frappe/frappe | ⭐ | Push needs FCM glue |\\n| 3 | Live events / video | **frappe/meet** (WebRTC) + LMS Zoom/BBB | github.com/frappe/meet, github.com/frappe/lms | 🟡 | No broadcast/webinar; **Teams integration is custom** (see ADR-003) |\\n| 4 | Member directory (public, filterable) | — (LMS profile is course-centric) | — | 🔴 | Build on Framework |\\n| 5 | Paywalls / membership tiers | frappe/payments + ERPNext Subscription | github.com/frappe/payments | 🟡 | No Space-gating UX |\\n| 6 | Email digests | frappe/newsletter | github.com/frappe/newsletter | 🟡 | Engine only, no \\\"this-week-in\\\" generator |\\n| 7 | Helpdesk / safeguarding tickets | **frappe/helpdesk** | github.com/frappe/helpdesk | ⭐ | None |\\n| 8 | Community moderation (word filters, AI flag, queues, appeals) | — | — | 🔴 | Build on Framework |\\n| 9 | Wiki / knowledge base | **frappe/wiki** | github.com/frappe/wiki | ⭐ | None |\\n| 10 | Polls / surveys | frappe/poll (abandoned 2016); LMS quizzes for course context | — | 🔴 | Build on Framework |\\n| 11 | Gamification / badges | **frappe/eps** (Energy Points) | github.com/frappe/eps | ⭐ | Points & leaderboards yes; visual badge UI no |\\n| 12 | Global search | Framework SQLite FTS5 (July 2025) | github.com/frappe/frappe | ⭐ | Cross-content wiring needed |\\n| 13 | Analytics / BI | **frappe/insights** | github.com/frappe/insights | ⭐ | No prebuilt community dashboards |\\n...\n  Line 10212:               \"text\": \"# ADR-0001 — Adopt the Frappe Framework + Gameplan + LMS as the FirstGens Community platform\\n\\nStructured against the UK Government's Architecture Decision Record (ADR)\\nframework as published on the GDS Technology Blog\\n(<https://technology.blog.gov.uk/2025/12/08/the-architecture-decision-record-adr-framework-making-better-technology-decisions-across-the-public-sector/>),\\nDecember 2025.\\n\\n| | |\\n| --- | --- |\\n| **ADR ID** | FG-ADR-0001 |\\n| **Status** | Proposed |\\n| **Date** | 2026-06-20 |\\n| **Decision owner** | FirstGens Technology Lead |\\n| **Stakeholders consulted** | Programme Director, Safeguarding Lead, Data Protection Officer, two student representatives, one mentor representative |\\n| **Supersedes** | — |\\n| **Superseded by** | — |\\n| **Review by** | 2027-06-20 (or sooner if a hosted vendor closes the gap to >90% feature parity at <50% TCO) |\\n\\n## 1. Context\\n\\nFirstGens is a community + learning programme for first-generation\\nuniversity students in the UK. The product surface required, validated\\nthrough the clickable prototype in this repo, includes:\\n\\n- A Circle.so-style feed of Spaces, Posts, Comments, Reactions\\n- Member directory and rich public profiles\\n- Events with RSVPs, including in-person, BigBlueButton and external links\\n- Mentor matching workflow (request, accept, active, closed)\\n- A real Learning Management surface (courses, chapters, lessons that can\\n  embed YouTube videos, enrolment, per-lesson completion tracking,\\n  certificates)\\n- Per-user notification + privacy settings\\n- Direct messaging\\n- Lightweight safeguarding: flagging of posts whose tone suggests a\\n  student in distress, with a moderator triage queue\\n- Public-sector friendly hosting story (UK-region, ISO 27001-aligned\\n  infra, full data export, no vendor lock-in)\\n\\nTwo architectural options were taken seriously:\\n\\n- **Option A — Hosted SaaS (Circle.so or similar):** fastest start, but\\n  per-seat pricing, US-region default, no LMS in ba...\n  Line 10221:             \"text\": \"# ADR-0001 — Adopt the Frappe Framework + Gameplan + LMS as the FirstGens Community platform\\n\\nStructured against the UK Government's Architecture Decision Record (ADR)\\nframework as published on the GDS Technology Blog\\n(<https://technology.blog.gov.uk/2025/12/08/the-architecture-decision-record-adr-framework-making-better-technology-decisions-across-the-public-sector/>),\\nDecember 2025.\\n\\n| | |\\n| --- | --- |\\n| **ADR ID** | FG-ADR-0001 |\\n| **Status** | Proposed |\\n| **Date** | 2026-06-20 |\\n| **Decision owner** | FirstGens Technology Lead |\\n| **Stakeholders consulted** | Programme Director, Safeguarding Lead, Data Protection Officer, two student representatives, one mentor representative |\\n| **Supersedes** | — |\\n| **Superseded by** | — |\\n| **Review by** | 2027-06-20 (or sooner if a hosted vendor closes the gap to >90% feature parity at <50% TCO) |\\n\\n## 1. Context\\n\\nFirstGens is a community + learning programme for first-generation\\nuniversity students in the UK. The product surface required, validated\\nthrough the clickable prototype in this repo, includes:\\n\\n- A Circle.so-style feed of Spaces, Posts, Comments, Reactions\\n- Member directory and rich public profiles\\n- Events with RSVPs, including in-person, BigBlueButton and external links\\n- Mentor matching workflow (request, accept, active, closed)\\n- A real Learning Management surface (courses, chapters, lessons that can\\n  embed YouTube videos, enrolment, per-lesson completion tracking,\\n  certificates)\\n- Per-user notification + privacy settings\\n- Direct messaging\\n- Lightweight safeguarding: flagging of posts whose tone suggests a\\n  student in distress, with a moderator triage queue\\n- Public-sector friendly hosting story (UK-region, ISO 27001-aligned\\n  infra, full data export, no vendor lock-in)\\n\\nTwo architectural options were taken seriously:\\n\\n- **Option A — Hosted SaaS (Circle.so or similar):** fastest start, but\\n  per-seat pricing, US-region default, no LMS in base...\n  Line 10228:           \"thinking\": \"The ADR content is exceptionally well-structured and directly references the UK GDS framework, citing a specific blog post URL from December 2025 that establishes credibility and shows this follows an established, real-world standard for architecture decision records.\\n\\nHowever, I'm noticing an inconsistency in the repository attribution — the document lists \\\"frappe/raven\\\" for the direct messaging tool, but the project's own planning docs correctly identify it as \\\"The-Commit-Company/Raven\\\" under an AGPL license, so there's a factual error in how the repository is credited within ADR-001 itself.\",\n\n  Line 10438:               \"summary\": \"Verifying repository attribution and scrutinizing AGPL licensing implications.\"\n\n  Line 10479:               \"text\": \"# ADR-002 — Direct messages via Raven\\n\\n- **Status:** Proposed\\n- **Date:** 2026-06-20\\n- **Review by:** 2027-06-20\\n- **Format:** UK GDS ADR (Dec 2025)\\n\\n## Context\\nFirstGens needs DMs, group chats, threaded replies, file sharing and mobile push. Circle.so provides these natively. Frappe Framework's legacy `frappe/chat` is deprecated (v13/v14 only).\\n\\n## Decision\\nAdopt **Raven** (github.com/The-Commit-Company/Raven, AGPL-3.0) as the messaging layer. Raven is the de-facto standard, has 6,400+ Frappe Cloud installs, an active React Native mobile app, and an AI bot framework. We will theme Raven to match the FG palette.\\n\\n## Status\\nProposed — pending licence review (AGPL implications for any closed-source FG modules).\\n\\n## Consequences\\n- **Positive:** Production-ready, mobile included, AI bots, no DM code to maintain.\\n- **Negative:** AGPL contagion risk for any code linked into Raven — keep all custom DM features in separate `fg_companion` app communicating via REST.\\n- Adds a Postgres/MariaDB tables footprint (~12 tables) and a Socket.IO dependency (already required by Frappe).\\n\\n## Alternatives considered\\n- **frappe/chat** — deprecated.\\n- **ClefinCode Chat** — fewer installs, less active.\\n- **Build our own** — wasteful; messaging is a commodity.\\n\\n## Frappe artefacts\\n- Repo: github.com/The-Commit-Company/Raven\\n- Install: `bench get-app raven && bench --site <site> install-app raven`\\n- Glue DocType: `fg_mentor_match` adds `raven_channel_id`, populated via `on_update` server script that calls `raven.api.channel.create_direct_message_channel`.\\n\\n## Gherkin acceptance\\nSee `docs/09_GHERKIN_UX_SCENARIOS.md` § 1.\\n\",\n\n  Line 10488:             \"text\": \"# ADR-002 — Direct messages via Raven\\n\\n- **Status:** Proposed\\n- **Date:** 2026-06-20\\n- **Review by:** 2027-06-20\\n- **Format:** UK GDS ADR (Dec 2025)\\n\\n## Context\\nFirstGens needs DMs, group chats, threaded replies, file sharing and mobile push. Circle.so provides these natively. Frappe Framework's legacy `frappe/chat` is deprecated (v13/v14 only).\\n\\n## Decision\\nAdopt **Raven** (github.com/The-Commit-Company/Raven, AGPL-3.0) as the messaging layer. Raven is the de-facto standard, has 6,400+ Frappe Cloud installs, an active React Native mobile app, and an AI bot framework. We will theme Raven to match the FG palette.\\n\\n## Status\\nProposed — pending licence review (AGPL implications for any closed-source FG modules).\\n\\n## Consequences\\n- **Positive:** Production-ready, mobile included, AI bots, no DM code to maintain.\\n- **Negative:** AGPL contagion risk for any code linked into Raven — keep all custom DM features in separate `fg_companion` app communicating via REST.\\n- Adds a Postgres/MariaDB tables footprint (~12 tables) and a Socket.IO dependency (already required by Frappe).\\n\\n## Alternatives considered\\n- **frappe/chat** — deprecated.\\n- **ClefinCode Chat** — fewer installs, less active.\\n- **Build our own** — wasteful; messaging is a commodity.\\n\\n## Frappe artefacts\\n- Repo: github.com/The-Commit-Company/Raven\\n- Install: `bench get-app raven && bench --site <site> install-app raven`\\n- Glue DocType: `fg_mentor_match` adds `raven_channel_id`, populated via `on_update` server script that calls `raven.api.channel.create_direct_message_channel`.\\n\\n## Gherkin acceptance\\nSee `docs/09_GHERKIN_UX_SCENARIOS.md` § 1.\\n\"\n\n  Line 10495:           \"thinking\": \"The Raven repository attribution checks out correctly with AGPL licensing noted, and the ADR appropriately flags this as pending license review since AGPL's network-use clause creates stronger copyleft obligations than standard GPL. Now I'm moving through the remaining entries.\",\n\n  Line 10769:           \"thinking\": \"Wait, I'm noticing something here — Gameplan actually already has GP Poll functionality built in. The gp_discussion.json file shows \\\"GP Poll\\\" as a valid option in the last_post_type field, and looking back at the doctypes I pulled earlier, Gameplan includes gp_poll, gp_poll_option, and gp_poll_vote. So this feature already exists in the system.\\n\\nBut ADR-007 is proposing to build a completely separate fg_poll and fg_poll_vote system from scratch — which means we'd have three different poll implementations across the architecture: Gameplan's native GP Poll, Raven's raven_poll system, and now this new custom fg_poll. That's a significant architectural redundancy that nobody's addressed yet, and it directly contradicts what ADR-001 already established about GP Discussion supporting polls. This is a concrete, well-evidenced inconsistency I should highlight in my synthesis.\\n\\nLet me keep pulling through the remaining ADRs to see what else is there.\",\n\n  Line 11014:             \"file_text\": \"# FirstGens Community Platform — Architecture & Product Decision Record\\n### Plain-English version, for Alaya and the wider FirstGens team\\n\\n**What this document is:** a synthesis of everything that's actually been built and decided in the Lovable prototype (project `d07c1ea6-a6f9-44ba-aad3-ad94dd714078`) — pulled directly from its real code and 12 markdown documents, not summarized from memory. Where a claim in the prototype's own docs turned out to be wrong or overstated when checked against the real open-source projects, that's flagged clearly below rather than smoothed over.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 1. The one-paragraph version\\n\\nWe're building FirstGens' community platform on **open-source, self-hosted software (Frappe Framework)** instead of paying for a commercial tool like Circle.so. This is what's normally called \\\"build vs. buy,\\\" and the case for \\\"build\\\" comes down to three things: it's roughly **6x cheaper at 5,000 members**, **all student data stays under FirstGens' own control** (important given we're working with a vulnerable, under-supported population), and **the learning/courses side is actually a real Frappe strength**, not an afterthought the way it is on Circle. The trade-off is real too: it takes longer to get the first version live, and needs someone who knows this stack.\\n\\nA clickable prototype already exists showing what the screens would look like. **No real student data is in it, and no production system has been built yet** — this is a blueprint, not a launch.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 2. What's been decided (in plain terms)\\n\\nThe platform is being assembled mostly from existing, free, open-source building blocks — not built from scratch. Think of it like furnishing a house with mostly off-the-shelf IKEA pieces, with a few custom-built items where nothing off-the-shelf fits.\\n\\n**Off-the-shelf pieces (just install and brand them):**\\n\\n| What students see | What it's built on | Confidence this works |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Discussion f...\n  Line 11021:             \"json_block\": \"{\\\"language\\\": \\\"markdown\\\", \\\"code\\\": \\\"# FirstGens Community Platform \\\\u2014 Architecture & Product Decision Record\\\\n### Plain-English version, for Alaya and the wider FirstGens team\\\\n\\\\n**What this document is:** a synthesis of everything that's actually been built and decided in the Lovable prototype (project `d07c1ea6-a6f9-44ba-aad3-ad94dd714078`) \\\\u2014 pulled directly from its real code and 12 markdown documents, not summarized from memory. Where a claim in the prototype's own docs turned out to be wrong or overstated when checked against the real open-source projects, that's flagged clearly below rather than smoothed over.\\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\n## 1. The one-paragraph version\\\\n\\\\nWe're building FirstGens' community platform on **open-source, self-hosted software (Frappe Framework)** instead of paying for a commercial tool like Circle.so. This is what's normally called \\\\\\\"build vs. buy,\\\\\\\" and the case for \\\\\\\"build\\\\\\\" comes down to three things: it's roughly **6x cheaper at 5,000 members**, **all student data stays under FirstGens' own control** (important given we're working with a vulnerable, under-supported population), and **the learning/courses side is actually a real Frappe strength**, not an afterthought the way it is on Circle. The trade-off is real too: it takes longer to get the first version live, and needs someone who knows this stack.\\\\n\\\\nA clickable prototype already exists showing what the screens would look like. **No real student data is in it, and no production system has been built yet** \\\\u2014 this is a blueprint, not a launch.\\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\n## 2. What's been decided (in plain terms)\\\\n\\\\nThe platform is being assembled mostly from existing, free, open-source building blocks \\\\u2014 not built from scratch. Think of it like furnishing a house with mostly off-the-shelf IKEA pieces, with a few custom-built items where nothing off-the-shelf fits.\\\\n\\\\n**Off-the-shelf pieces (just install and brand them):**\\\\n\\\\n| ...\n  Line 11150:           \"thinking\": \"I need to add a critical path section to the document that explains the concept from scratch for Alaya, covering what it is, where it comes from methodologically, and then applying it specifically to the FirstGens Community Platform project.\\n\\nThe critical path is the longest sequence of dependent tasks that determines the minimum project duration—if any task on it slips, the whole project is delayed. This comes from the Critical Path Method (CPM), developed in the late 1950s by Morgan R. Walker at DuPont and James E. Kelley Jr. at Remington Rand as a formal project scheduling technique. I'll need to map out the actual dependency chains across our work packages and ADRs to identify which sequence of tasks is truly critical to launch and which can happen in parallel without affecting the timeline.\\n\\nNow I'm reviewing the work packages we've already established—infrastructure provisioning, Frappe/LMS setup, Frappe/Gameplan with the registration model decision, the custom fg_companion app, the deferrable AI features, visual cohesion, testing, UAT, and deployment—plus the additional scope from Lovable like Raven, Helpdesk, Wiki, and the custom pieces like member directory, mentor matching, and moderation. I need to trace which of these actually block others and which can run in parallel, then identify the three open decisions that might affect the critical path.\\n\\nLooking at the decision list, the paywall question is genuinely cheap to resolve and could eliminate work entirely, the poll system redundancy is trivial, and the Raven repo issue is just a labeling fix. But the cohort age range and safeguarding framework decision is potentially critical because it gates the moderation design, and the AI Gateway production dependency confusion needs clarification since it could affect how we architect the backend. The AGPL license review for Raven could also block adoption if there's a conflict. Let me map out which of these actually sit on the critic...\n  Line 11943:           \"text\": \"[NOTE: This conversation was successfully compacted to free up space in the context window. This is a summary of the content that was discussed prior to compaction. The full uncompacted conversation is stored in a transcript file which is accessible via both the read tool and the bash tool. I (the assistant) should use it whenever I need to revisit details from previous parts of the conversation. I should do it incrementally as the transcript may be massive!]\\n[Transcript: /mnt/transcripts/2026-06-20-10-37-30-firstgens-frappe-architecture-gherkin.txt]\\n[Description: Extended multi-session thread building FirstGens UK's community platform architecture: Frappe/Gameplan/LMS technical decisions, a Lovable AI-built prototype audit, multiple stakeholder-facing markdown deliverables (ARD/PRD, critical path, Gherkin/Frappe TCO-FinOps), and ongoing discovery work mining the user's past conversation history for genuine FirstGens requirements (mid-search, with a critical disambiguation against an unrelated venture called \\\"Progress\\\").]\\n[For a catalog of previous transcripts see journal.txt in the same directory]\\n[Full summary below:]\\n\\n**Context:** User (Andie/Andrea Kwabena Enning) building FirstGens UK's community platform (Alaya Holloway's non-profit for first-gen students), potentially as paid/equity technical lead. ~5hrs/week capacity.\\n\\n**[DECISION] Core architecture (established and re-verified across the session):** `frappe/lms` (unmodified, real repo) + `frappe/gameplan` (unmodified, real repo — provides Spaces/Discussions/Comments/Reactions/Polls natively) + small custom `fg_companion` app (Events/RSVP, Mentor Match, AI hooks via Custom Fields on `GP Discussion`/`GP Comment`, NOT new DocTypes on Gameplan). Verified directly against cloned repos at `/home/claude/frappe-research/` (gameplan, lms, raven, eps, payments, frappe-core, wiki, helpdesk): `GP Reaction` is a real child table (`istable:1`) on both `GP Discussion` and `GP Comment`; `GP Dis...\n  Line 12007:           \"thinking\": \"The user is clarifying the poll system approach—they want to use Gameplan's native poll functionality instead of creating a custom one, which eliminates the redundancy I'd identified across the three different poll implementations.\\n\\nThey're also asking for three things to be added to the document: an explanation of UAT (what it is, its origins, and current usage), and an assessment of whether ADRs and Gherkin .feature files are actually necessary for this project going forward. I should evaluate whether these documentation approaches still make sense given the project's scope and needs.\\n\\nThere's also a technical question about whether Gherkin BDD testing even works with the Frappe framework, which I'll need to verify rather than assume. All of this should go into an appendix section that I'll add to the existing document structure.\\n\\nFor the poll decision itself, I need to update section 4 where the three poll systems issue was flagged as needing resolution, and also revise the critical path section to reflect that this is now decided—Gameplan's native GP Poll is the choice, with the custom fg_poll plan dropped and Raven's poll feature disabled to avoid duplication.\\n\\nI should also note that ADR-007 from the original Lovable build (which proposed building a custom fg_poll) should be marked as superseded by this decision.\\n\\nFor the UAT explanation in the appendix, I'm thinking through the origins of User Acceptance Testing—it doesn't have a single inventor like some methodologies, but rather evolved from the Waterfall model and broader software engineering practices in the 1970s as a formal QA stage within the SDLC. before software existed in manufacturing and engineering contexts. The V-Model formalized in Germany during the 1980s-90s explicitly positioned UAT as the validation phase mirroring requirements, while modern Agile practices have integrated it differently through sprint reviews and stakeholder sign-offs. Rather than having a ...\n  Line 12813:             \"new_str\": \"1. ~~Three different \\\"polls\\\" systems got planned, accidentally, on top of each other.~~ **RESOLVED.** Decision made: use Gameplan's built-in poll feature (`GP Poll`) as the only poll system. The custom `fg_poll`/`fg_poll_vote` build proposed in ADR-007 is rejected — it would have duplicated something that already exists. Raven's separate poll feature should simply go unused for community-facing polls, to avoid the same duplication on a second front. This removes an entire item from the build-from-scratch list in the gap analysis, which is a net reduction in work, not just a tidier plan.\",\n\n  Line 13138:           \"text\": \"Summary of what changed:\\n\\n**Poll decision** — resolved in Section 4: Gameplan's native `GP Poll` wins, the custom `fg_poll` build (ADR-007) is rejected outright, and Raven's separate poll feature goes unused. This isn't just a tidier plan — it deletes a whole item from the build-from-scratch list.\\n\\n**Appendix A (UAT)** — no single inventor, unlike critical path. It's software's adoption of a much older general \\\"customer inspects and accepts delivered work\\\" tradition, formalized in the V-Model where it explicitly closes the loop back to the original requirements stage.\\n\\n**Appendix B (ADR)** — traced to Michael Nygard's 15 November 2011 Cognitect blog post, still the most-used format 14 years later. On whether this project needs them: yes, with the receipts — the poll redundancy, the paywall scope-mismatch, and the AI Gateway mix-up were all caught *because* they were written down, not by looking at running code.\\n\\n**Appendix C (Gherkin)** — traced through Dan North (2003, coined BDD) → North & Chris Matts (2004, Given/When/Then) → Aslak Hellesøy (2008, built Cucumber, named Gherkin after his fiancée's pun). And the direct technical answer you asked for: **no, Gherkin doesn't work with Frappe natively** — Frappe's own docs are built entirely around Python's `unittest`/`FrappeTestCase`, with no official BDD integration anywhere. It's technically bolt-on-able via `behave`/`pytest-bdd`, but that's real unbuilt engineering work, not something free. Worth knowing: this matches how the `.feature` files have actually been used in this project already — as readable specs for sign-off, which is literally what Hellesøy says Gherkin was for in the first place, not a fallback.\",\n\n  Line 13728:           \"text\": \"Honestly, neither framing is quite right — and the actual answer matters because the two things you're contrasting would lead to very different conclusions about how reliable any of this is.\\n\\n**It's not really \\\"stakeholder question prompting.\\\"** That's a real, useful technique — structuring information around what a non-technical reader would actually ask (\\\"is it the architecture or not,\\\" \\\"what's actually built vs. just planned\\\") — but that's a *presentation* skill. It makes accurate information legible. It does nothing to make inaccurate information accurate. You could use that exact same framing technique to deliver confident, well-organized, completely wrong answers — which is more or less what the original Gemini document did when it invented a GetAway founder. Clean structure and a fabricated fact sit together just fine.\\n\\n**C2 English is necessary but not the source of it either.** What it actually buys is the ability to hold and express fine distinctions — \\\"confirmed against the live repo\\\" vs. \\\"plausible but I haven't checked\\\" vs. \\\"directly contradicted by what I found\\\" are different claims, and saying them precisely requires real command of hedging, modality, and register. But that's the *vehicle*, not the engine. Fluent language lets you state a wrong fact just as smoothly as a right one.\\n\\n**What actually did the work, mechanically, was going and checking.** Concretely, in this conversation: cloning the real `frappe/gameplan` and `frappe/lms` repos and reading the actual DocType JSON instead of trusting what a document claimed about them; web-searching to confirm a specific GitHub repo path existed before using it; re-verifying a claim about `GP Project`'s `members` field against the literal source file rather than my own memory of having checked it earlier. The precision came from treating *specific, confident-sounding claims* as exactly the kind of thing most likely to be subtly wrong, and then actually testing that sus...\n  Line 13773:           \"thinking\": \"The user is asking whether I've accumulated enough context about the FirstGens project to write high-fidelity Gherkin feature files that serve as specification documents, as they mentioned in an earlier document.\\n\\nThey're also asking about VS Code tooling for .feature files—specifically whether there's a nice syntax-highlighting extension and if I can provide links to videos or blog posts demonstrating it.\\n\\nFor the first part, I'm thinking through what I've learned in this conversation: I now have the actual Gameplan schema with real entities like GP Project, GP Discussion, GP Comment, and GP Reaction, which is substantially more concrete than when I wrote those initial six feature files. I could rewrite the Gherkin scenarios now with much higher fidelity—using the actual field names I've verified, the resolved decisions like GP Poll only, and explicitly marking what's still open like the registration model. But I'm hitting a real constraint: true business-readable Gherkin requires agreed behavior, and since the registration and membership model is genuinely unresolved, any scenario touching access control or student enrollment would either need to be flagged as TBD or rest on an assumption I haven't validated.\\n\\nSo the practical move is to offer upgrading the existing feature files with everything that IS settled—Spaces as GP Projects, Posts with real field names, reactions as child tables, polls via GP Poll only—while explicitly calling out which scenarios are blocked by the open decisions.\\n\\nFor the VS Code tooling piece, I need to actually verify what's available rather than assume. There's definitely a well-known Gherkin extension out there, but I should check what it actually provides before recommending it. I should search for the current VS Code extensions and real tutorial links to verify what's actually available now rather than relying on potentially outdated information from my training data.\",\n\n  Line 13798:           \"text\": \"Both good questions — let me actually answer the first honestly with specifics, then verify the VS Code tooling rather than recite something from memory that might be stale.\\n\\nOn entropy of information: genuinely, yes — meaningfully more than when I wrote the original 6 `.feature` files. Compare what I knew then vs. now:\\n\\n| | Original 6 `.feature` files | What I'd write now |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Field names | Guessed/generic (`space`, `body`) | Verified real (`project`, `content` — confirmed against the live `gp_discussion.json`) |\\n| Reactions | Assumed a separate linked record | Known to be a child table (`istable: 1`) on both Discussion and Comment |\\n| Polls | Didn't address it | Resolved decision: `GP Poll` only, `fg_poll` and Raven's poll explicitly rejected |\\n| Comments | Assumed a `title` field might exist | Confirmed it doesn't |\\n\\nSo for everything that's actually *settled* — Spaces, Posts, Comments, reactions, polls, the LMS-course-to-Space link — I could write scenarios now that are genuinely higher-fidelity, not just better-worded. But there's a real limit, and it's not a knowledge gap, it's that some things this project hasn't decided yet: the registration/membership model, the cohort age range, the paywall question. Writing confident Gherkin for those would mean inventing an answer to a question still marked open — exactly the failure mode this whole project has been catching elsewhere. The honest version is scenarios for the settled parts, and explicit \\\"Background: blocked on [decision]\\\" placeholders for the rest, not pretend-resolved ones.\\n\\nSay the word and I'll actually rewrite the set properly rather than just describe the improvement.\\n\\nOn VS Code tooling — let me check the current real extension and find an actual demo rather than guess from memory:\",\n\n  Line 14299:           \"thinking\": \"The user is pushing back on my earlier point about not writing Gherkin scenarios for unresolved decisions. They're suggesting that even with open questions, we could draft something plausible that stakeholders could review and refine, rather than leaving those scenarios blank entirely.\\n\\nThat's actually a solid practical approach — it's the strawman proposal technique, where you write a draft assumption explicitly labeled as such to unblock analysis paralysis. This directly connects to Example Mapping, which has a specific category for \\\"assumptions we're choosing to make in order to progress.\\\" it as settled fact. The real distinction is transparency: a labeled draft assumption invites refinement and signals its provisional status, whereas silently treating an open question as resolved in confident Gherkin creates false certainty. This is exactly what Example Mapping's assumption card already formalizes — a way to document \\\"we're choosing to move forward with this, pending confirmation\\\" rather than pretending the question never existed.\\n\\nI'm thinking I should offer to write those Gherkin scenarios now for the three open items (registration model, cohort age, paywall) with explicit \\\"ASSUMPTION\\\" labels so Alaya can react to concrete drafts rather than abstract placeholders. Given how this conversation has gone, they'd likely want me to proceed directly.\\n\\nFor the registration model, I'd draft a scenario based on the most open-community-friendly option I mentioned earlier — students self-registering with a verified university email and being auto-added to a single FirstGens GP Team as members, which aligns with FirstGens' actual mission.\\n\\nFor the cohort age range and safeguarding question, I'm genuinely uncertain whether FirstGens serves under-18s or just enrolled university students. The organization's core mission is supporting first-generation university students (typically 18+), but I should probably default to the more conservativ...\n  Line 14671:               \"text\": \"<chat url=\\\"https://claude.ai/chat/e1aa2337-17c8-4679-9962-ee304d6b8561\\\" updated_at=\\\"2025-07-01T15:53:30.696186+00:00\\\"><untrusted_external_data source=\\\"past_conversation\\\">Title: Meeting Transcripts Review\\nMeeting Transcripts Review\\n&lt;chat_conversation&gt;Title: Meeting Transcripts Review\\n\\nHuman: Okay so lets start with these ones but im not done got a coupla more.\\n\\nAssistant: I can see you've shared 6 meeting transcripts from Progress, a mentorship platform company, spanning from June 9-23, 2025, plus one from May 16. These appear to be internal team meetings discussing:\\n\\n**Key Context I'm gathering:**\\n- **Progress** is a mentorship platform connecting young people (18-30) from underrepresented backgrounds with mentors via 12-minute video calls\\n- **Main participants**: Andre (CEO), Andrea/Andie (Product Manager), Hurera (Developer), Hashir (Tech Lead), Olu (QA/Tester), Anthony\\n- **Current challenges**: App stability issues, testing bottlenecks, admin panel limitations, environment separation needs\\n- **Business focus**: Corporate partnerships (Virgin, O2, etc.), fundraising efforts, scaling to 10K+ users\\n- **Competitors**: Pushfar, BYP Network, others mentioned in competitive analysis\\n\\n**Major themes across meetings:**\\n1. Technical debt and stability issues (app crashes, messaging bugs, timezone problems)\\n2. Product development roadmap (reverse mentoring, corporate mentee codes, white-labeling)\\n3. Testing and QA process improvements\\n4. Team coordination and communication challenges\\n5. Fundraising preparation and market positioning\\n\\nI'm ready for your additional documents. Once you've shared everything, let me know:\\n- What specific analysis or insights you're looking for\\n- Whether you need help with particular aspects (strategy, technical issues, team dynamics, etc.)\\n- Any specific questions or problems you'd like me to focus on\\n\\nWhat would be most helpful for you with this material?\\n\\nHuman: these were the fin...\n  Line 14861:               \"text\": \"<chat url=\\\"https://claude.ai/chat/7def0c5c-1a0b-4356-9b23-17477a97e9e1\\\" updated_at=\\\"2025-01-13T12:02:15.017088+00:00\\\"><untrusted_external_data source=\\\"past_conversation\\\">Title: Positioning a Platform for First-Gen Students\\nPositioning a Platform for First-Gen Students\\nThe `:milestone` property signifies the crucial public launch milestone in Jan 2026.\\n\\nBy visualizing the roadmap in this way, Alaya and her stakeholders can get a clear, quarter-by-quarter view of the development journey for 2025. The chart emphasizes the importance of the initial requirements gathering and design phase in Q1, the intense development period in Q2-Q3, and the ramp up to launch in Q4.\\n\\nPresenting the roadmap in this visually engaging way will help Alaya build alignment and excitement around the Firstgen platform vision and plan as she drives the initiative forward in 2025.&lt;/chat_conversation&gt;</untrusted_external_data></chat>\\n\\n<chat url=\\\"https://claude.ai/chat/7def0c5c-1a0b-4356-9b23-17477a97e9e1\\\" updated_at=\\\"2025-01-13T12:02:15.017088+00:00\\\"><untrusted_external_data source=\\\"past_conversation\\\">Title: Positioning a Platform for First-Gen Students\\nPositioning a Platform for First-Gen Students\\nThe `:milestone` property signifies the crucial public launch milestone in Jan 2026.\\n\\nBy visualizing the roadmap in this way, Alaya and her stakeholders can get a clear, quarter-by-quarter view of the development journey for 2025. The chart emphasizes the importance of the initial requirements gathering and design phase in Q1, the intense development period in Q2-Q3, and the ramp up to launch in Q4.\\n\\nPresenting the roadmap in this visually engaging way will help Alaya build alignment and excitement around the Firstgen platform vision and plan as she drives the initiative forward in 2025.</untrusted_external_data></chat>\\n\\n<chat url=\\\"https://claude.ai/chat/8a68e1f0-64cc-4350-9ec7-587c34e11858\\\" updated_at=\\\"2025-01-13T14:06:22.850444+00:00\\\"><untr...\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\StefaniaOkereke\\06_technical_architecture_decisions_audit.md:\n  Line 23: **Context in the document:** Repeatedly states \"Frappe is fully open-source under GPL-v3\" (e.g., the TCO table, the maintainability discussion) as part of arguing there's no future paywall risk.\n\n  Line 25: **Claim:** Frappe = GPL-v3.\n\n  Line 27: **Verdict: Imprecise, conflates two different repos.** I checked GitHub directly: the **Frappe Framework** itself (`frappe/frappe`) is licensed **MIT** — a permissive license with no copyleft obligations. **ERPNext**, the specific application built on top of the framework, is the one licensed **GPL-3.0**. If FirstGens builds a custom Frappe app (not ERPNext itself), it's building on MIT-licensed infrastructure, which is actually a *stronger* \"no future paywall risk\" guarantee than GPL would have given, since MIT doesn't even require derivative works to stay open-source. The document's underlying conclusion (\"no licensing risk\") happens to land in the right place, but for an imprecise/wrong reason — worth correcting if you're citing this to a grant panel or partner, since \"GPL-v3\" and \"MIT\" carry genuinely different legal obligations.\n\n  Line 112: | Frappe licensed GPL-v3 | **Imprecise** — framework is MIT, ERPNext is GPL-3.0 | 95% |\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\StefaniaOkereke\\10_ALAYA_ARD_PRD_SYNTHESIS.md:\n  Line 60: 1. ~~Three different \"polls\" systems got planned, accidentally, on top of each other.~~ **RESOLVED.** Decision made: use Gameplan's built-in poll feature (`GP Poll`) as the only poll system. The custom `fg_poll`/`fg_poll_vote` build proposed in ADR-007 is rejected — it would have duplicated something that already exists. Raven's separate poll feature should simply go unused for community-facing polls, to avoid the same duplication on a second front. This removes an entire item from the build-from-scratch list in the gap analysis, which is a net reduction in work, not just a tidier plan.\n\n  Line 72: 7. **The chat tool (Raven) uses a stricter open-source licence (AGPL) than the rest of the stack.** This isn't a blocker, but it does mean: anything we build that talks *directly* to Raven's code (rather than just calling it over the network) could be legally required to also be open-sourced. The prototype's own plan already flags this correctly and proposes keeping our custom code separate to avoid it — that's the right call, just worth you knowing it's a real legal consideration, not a hypothetical one.\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\Platform Scaling And Documentation Refinement.md:\n  Line 511:    - Event listeners in `hooks.py` to trigger background jobs on GP Discussions/Comments.\n\n  Line 535: 1. **Frontend (`src/data/store.ts`)**: We routed the entire data layer to [src/data/store.ts](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/community-launchpad-proto/src/data/store.ts). If a Frappe bench backend is running, it will automatically connect to it and perform real API actions (e.g. `GET /api/resource/GP Discussion`, `POST /api/method/fg_companion.api.rsvp`). If there is no server running, it falls back seamlessly to the in-memory mock store so you can still preview and run the frontend standalone.\n\n\n(Results truncated: showing 100 of 25156 matches (25056 hidden). Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)",
