      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\PIP Re-application\\PIP&Laura.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: User: hi\n2: Model: Hi there! How can I help you today?\n3: User: why was i sent this?\n4: Model: You were sent these documents as part of the process related to a **Personal Independence Payment (PIP) claim** for Deborah Ennin.\n5: \n6: Specifically, the \"PIP.7011 Enhanced Disallowance Letter\" (pages 58-62) is a formal communication from the Department for Work & Pensions (DWP) stating that **PIP has not been awarded** for both daily living and mobility needs from October 13, 2021. This letter explains the decision and outlines the process for requesting a mandatory reconsideration if you disagree with the outcome.\n7: \n8: The other documents you received, such as the SSCS1 form (pages 2-4), the PIP2 questionnaire (pages 5-17), medical reports (pages 24-28, 29-31, 65-73), and the PIP consultation report (pages 34-58), are all the supporting evidence and assessments that were considered by the DWP when making the decision about the PIP claim. The \"Mandatory Reconsideration Request\" (pages 63-64) is a request made on behalf of Deborah Ennin to reconsider the DWP's decision.\n9: User: This is what happened in the past and now this is what I have been brought to do? So? Should i be alerted or i should just look through my nhs notes, compare and constrast what was written in this old version and the transcribe in the new one the diffs by bringing in new details and to mantain the amount being recived maintain the scores or alter them slightly in the favour of what the current notes say which if u even taken the current one from the old case it should tell you that it wouldn’t vastly change cause is chronic no? Or?\n10: Model: You've been sent a **Personal Independence Payment (PIP) review form** (PIP.1043, pages 1-32 of the new document). This is a standard process because you were previously awarded PIP, and the Department for Work & Pensions (DWP) needs to check if your health condition or disability still affects you in the same way, more so, or less so.\n11: \n12: Here's how to interpret what you've received and how to approach it:\n13: \n14: ### Should You Be Alerted?\n15: \n16: You shouldn't be alarmed, but you should take this review very seriously. A PIP review is an opportunity for the DWP to reassess your entitlement. The outcome could mean your PIP award stays the same, increases, decreases, or stops. It's crucial to provide a comprehensive and accurate picture of your current difficulties.\n17: \n18: ### How to Approach the Review Form: Compare and Contrast with Old Notes\n19: \n20: Your approach to comparing your old and new NHS notes, and contrasting with the old PIP application, is absolutely correct and essential.\n21: \n22: 1.  **Review the Original PIP Application and Decision:**\n23:     *   Look back at the **PIP2 questionnaire** you submitted (pages 5-17 of the previous document). This outlines what you originally told the DWP about your conditions and how they affected you.\n24:     *   Crucially, refer to the **\"PIP.7011 Enhanced Disallowance Letter\"** (pages 58-62 of the previous document). This letter explicitly states *why* PIP was not awarded, detailing the DWP's conclusions on each activity. For example, it noted that you could prepare and cook a simple meal unaided, wash and bathe unaided, and manage toilet needs unaided, despite you reporting difficulties. It also noted a discrepancy regarding dizziness medication and specialist referrals.\n25:     *   Also, consider the **\"Reasons for appealing\"** on page 3 of the SSCS1 form (previous document). This summary highlights the key difficulties you reported, such as needing a chair for cooking, help with applying creams, difficulties with bathing/showering (small shower, sitting on a chair), needing support for toilet needs, assistance for dressing your lower half, and limited walking ability (20-50m slowly).\n26: \n27: 2.  **Analyze Current NHS Notes (including the Universal Credit Medical Report):**\n28:     *   The **Universal Credit Medical Report (UC85)** (pages 67-72 of the previous document), dated January 18, 2022, is particularly relevant as it's more recent than your initial PIP application and the disallowance letter.\n29:     *   Pay close attention to the \"Description of Functional Ability\" on pages 67-69. It states that after your stroke, you had bilateral leg pain, back pain, dizziness, balance, and fatigue. It explicitly mentions that your \"back and leg pain seems to have got worse\" and that your \"fatigue had improved after having the stroke but in the last month it has got worse and it is now constant and more severe.\" It also notes \"constant mild dizziness but twice a week she has more severe dizziness where she has to lie down for the day.\" These are significant points as they contradict some of the DWP's reasoning for disallowing your previous PIP claim, which mentioned no current medication for dizziness or referrals to a specialist.\n30:     *   The report also details your \"Typical Day\" (page 70), including getting up late, spending most of the day lying on the sofa due to dizziness, pain, and fatigue, walking limited distances (20m at a time) before needing to stop, and your daughter doing cleaning and food shopping due to your pain, dizziness, and fatigue. It mentions you batch cook once a week and need to rest for hours afterwards. You manage to wash and dress independently, but only twice a week, staying in nightwear other days.\n31:     *   Gather any other new or updated medical evidence you have since these documents, as the review form specifically asks for information \"since we last looked at your award\" (which would have been based on the older information).\n32: \n33: ### Maintaining Scores vs. Accurate Reporting\n34: \n35: *   **Focus on Accuracy:** Your primary goal should be to accurately describe your current functional abilities and the difficulties you experience across the 12 daily living and mobility activities. Do not try to artificially \"maintain scores.\"\n36: *   **Highlight Changes:** If your condition has worsened, or if you now require more help, aids, or supervision than when you last applied, this needs to be clearly and comprehensively explained. The UC85 report indicates that some of your symptoms (back/leg pain, dizziness, fatigue) have worsened, which is critical.\n37: *   **Chronic Condition Doesn't Guarantee Same Outcome:** While your conditions may be chronic, the *impact* of those conditions can change over time. The DWP's review is precisely to determine if your *needs* have changed. Even with a chronic condition, your functional abilities can fluctuate, improve, or deteriorate. The UC85 itself states that your pain and fatigue have worsened in the month prior to that report, and your dizziness is severe twice a week. This means your needs may indeed be greater now than when the DWP last assessed you, which could lead to a higher award if properly evidenced.\n38: \n39: ### What to Do Next:\n40: \n41: 1.  **Complete the Review Form (PIP.1043) in Detail:**\n42:     *   Go through each of the 12 activities listed in Section 5 (pages 16-28) of the new review form.\n43:     *   For each activity, describe **what you can and cannot do**, **why** (due to pain, dizziness, fatigue, balance, weakness), **how often** this difficulty occurs (e.g., \"on most days,\" \"twice a week\"), **what aids or assistance** you need, and **how long** it takes you.\n44:     *   **Provide specific examples** from your daily life, drawing on the details from the UC85 report (e.g., needing to sit on a perching stool to cook and resting for hours afterward due to fatigue; daughter doing cleaning and shopping; only dressing twice a week; walking 20m and needing to stop due to pain, dizziness, and fatigue).\n45:     *   **Directly address the points of disagreement from the previous PIP disallowance letter.** If the DWP previously said you could do something unaided, but now you can't, or need help, explain the change and why.\n46:     *   **Use the additional sheets** if you need more space for any answer. Remember to put your name and National Insurance number on every extra sheet.\n47: \n48: 2.  **Gather Supporting Evidence:**\n49:     *   Send **copies** (never originals) of all relevant medical evidence, especially anything new since your last PIP application. This includes the Universal Credit Medical Report (UC85) you have, as it details worsening symptoms.\n50:     *   Other useful documents include updated prescription lists, letters from specialists, physiotherapy reports, or any other professional who can comment on your current functional abilities. The review form (page 6) gives examples of what to send and what not to send.\n51: \n52: 3.  **Explain Any Discrepancies:**\n53:     *   If there are differences between what was previously stated (e.g., in the PIP disallowance letter) and your current situation or the UC85 report, clearly explain these. For instance, the disallowance letter mentioned no current medication for dizziness or referrals to a specialist for it, but the UC85 mentions \"constant mild dizziness but twice a week she has more severe dizziness where she has to lie down for the day\" and a worsening of symptoms. This is a crucial point to elaborate on.\n54: \n55: 4.  **Consider Getting Help:**\n56:     *   The DWP letter explicitly states you can ask a friend, relative, or a local support organization (like Welfare Rights) to help you fill out the form. Given the complexity and importance, seeking assistance from someone experienced with PIP applications can be very beneficial.\n57: \n58: By providing clear, detailed, and consistent information, backed by recent medical evidence, you can ensure the DWP has the most accurate picture of how your conditions currently affect your daily life and mobility.\n59: User: The UC85 report indicates\n60: whats that?\n61: Model: Based on the documents you provided, the **UC85 report** refers to the **Universal Credit Medical Report Form**.\n62: \n63: It's a medical assessment that was completed by a healthcare professional (Miss Bethany Lord, a Registered Physiotherapist and Approved Disability Analyst) on January 18, 2022, to assess your functional abilities for Universal Credit purposes. This report details:\n64: \n65: *   **Medical Conditions and Treatment:** Including identified conditions like Stroke, Diabetes, and Hypertension, and the medications you are prescribed.\n66: *   **Description of Functional Ability:** This section outlines how your conditions affect you, including details about pain, dizziness, fatigue, balance, and mobility. It also describes a \"Typical Day\" to illustrate the impact of your conditions on daily living.\n67: *   **Medical Examination Findings:** Though in your case, a telephone assessment was conducted due to the pandemic, so no physical examination was carried out for the Lower Limb.\n68: *   **LCW and LCWRA Information:** It concludes whether you meet the criteria for Limited Capability for Work and Work Related Activity.\n69: \n70: Essentially, it's a healthcare professional's assessment of how your health conditions affect your ability to carry out various tasks, which is used by the DWP to make decisions about benefits like Universal Credit. In your case, it's also a valuable piece of evidence for your PIP review as it describes your ongoing difficulties.\n71: User: should i be sending these old medical evidences or should i only send the ones that are pertinent and include then newer ones from say https://www.nhsapp.service.nhs.uk/login or https://access.login.nhs.uk/login\n72: Model: You're asking a very important and practical question for your PIP review!\n73: \n74: Based on the instructions in the new PIP review form (PIP.1043, specifically page 6), here's the best approach:\n75: \n76: 1.  **Do NOT send information you have already sent before to the DWP for your previous PIP claim.** The form explicitly states: \"do not send us copies of anything you have already sent us before.\" This is because they should already have it on file.\n77: \n78: 2.  **Focus on sending PERTINENT and NEWER medical evidence.** The review is about \"how your health condition or disability affects you *now*.\"\n79:     *   **The UC85 report (Universal Credit Medical Report Form from January 2022) is highly pertinent and should be sent.** While it's from 2022, it's a comprehensive medical assessment that describes your functional abilities and, crucially, highlights that some symptoms (back and leg pain, dizziness, fatigue) were worsening at that time. This directly addresses the DWP's previous disallowance reasons which stated no current medication for dizziness or referrals to a specialist. It serves as strong evidence of your condition's impact after your previous PIP assessment.\n80:     *   **Yes, absolutely obtain and include any NEWER medical evidence from sources like the NHS App/NHS Login.** This is exactly what the DWP is looking for.\n81:         *   **What to look for from the NHS App/Login:**\n82:             *   **Updated Summary Care Record/GP Notes:** These will show your current diagnoses, ongoing treatments, and any recent consultations where you discussed your symptoms and their impact.\n83:             *   **Recent Clinic Letters from Specialists:** If you've seen a neurologist, physiotherapist, occupational therapist, or any other specialist since early 2022 (when the UC85 was done), their letters will provide current insights.\n84:             *   **Latest Prescription Lists:** To show all your current medications and dosages.\n85:             *   **Recent Test Results:** Any scans, blood tests, or other diagnostic results that shed light on your condition.\n86:             *   **Physiotherapy or Rehabilitation Reports:** These are valuable as they directly comment on your functional abilities and limitations.\n87: \n88: **In summary:**\n89: \n90: *   **Definitely send:** The **UC85 report (Universal Credit Medical Report Form from January 2022)** you have, and **any and all new medical evidence** you can gather from your GP, specialists, or the NHS App/Login that reflects your current health and how it impacts your daily living and mobility.\n91: *   **Do NOT send:** Documents that were part of your *original* PIP application and decision (e.g., the Medical Discharge Summary from Nov/Dec 2020, Patient Summary: Medication list from Jan 2021, if these haven't changed significantly or are superseded by newer evidence). The DWP already has these.\n92: \n93: **Crucial Steps for Submitting Evidence:**\n94: \n95: *   **Send COPIES ONLY:** Never send original documents.\n96: *   **Write your full name and National Insurance number** clearly at the top of every single page of supporting evidence you send.\n97: *   **Refer to the question number** on the PIP review form that each piece of evidence supports, if possible.\n98: *   **Do not delay sending the review form** if you are waiting for new evidence. Send what you have by the deadline (12 March 2026) and explain on the form that further evidence will follow. Then send the additional evidence as soon as you get it, again with your name and NI number on each page, and note that it relates to your ongoing review.\n99: User: cool so the last time they had something from me now was back in?\n100: Model: Based on the documents you've provided, the last time they had something submitted from you related to your previous PIP claim was on **23 August 2022**, when the **appeal to the HM Courts & Tribunals Service (SSCS1 form)** was submitted.\n101: \n102: Before that, your **Mandatory Reconsideration Request** was dated **24th March 2022**. And the original **PIP2 questionnaire** was submitted on **30 November 2021**.\n103: User: so then anything from after march 2022 till now? will be greately appreciated no matter how much it is ?\n104: Model: Yes, that's absolutely correct and a great way to think about it!\n105: \n106: Anything new and relevant from **after March 2022 up until now (April 2026)** will be greatly appreciated by the DWP. This is the period they are particularly interested in for your review, as it shows how your condition has progressed and is currently affecting you *since their last decision*.\n107: \n108: **No matter how much it is, send it.** Even small pieces of evidence can collectively build a stronger picture of your daily challenges.\n109: \n110: Remember to:\n111: *   Send **copies only**.\n112: *   Write your **full name and National Insurance number** on every single page of the evidence you send.\n113: \n114: This new evidence will be crucial in demonstrating the ongoing impact of your health conditions on your daily living and mobility activities.\n115: User: any good?\n116: \n117: Skip navigation\n118: Hucknall Road Medical Centre \n119: ProfileHelpLog out\n120: Home\n121:  Diary\n122:  Appointments\n123: Appointments \n124: Journal\n125: Appointments\n126: Appointments your teams have added to your record. You can also add appointments for your own reference.\n127: \n128: Past\n129: Sherwood Forest Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust\n130: Hospital Face to Face Appointment\n131: 19 February 2026 at 14:10\n132: Location: Clinic 8, King's Treatment Centre, King's Mill Hospital\n133: Specialty: Ophthalmology\n134: General health\n135: Churchside Medical Practice (Responsible organisation: Churchside Medical Practice) Released by GP Practice\n136: CHRONIC DISEASE REVIEW\n137: 02 February 2026 at 09:00\n138: Location: Churchside Medical Practice\n139: Attendees: Mrs Zoe Udall\n140: General health\n141: Churchside Medical Practice (Responsible organisation: Churchside Medical Practice) Released by GP Practice\n142: CHRONIC DISEASE REVIEW\n143: 07 January 2026 at 08:00\n144: Location: Churchside Medical Practice\n145: Attendees: Mrs Zoe U