      "code": "{\"command\": \"try { Add-Type -AssemblyName \\\"DocumentFormat.OpenXml\\\"; } catch {} ; if (Get-Command python -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue) { python -c \\\"import zipfile, re; z=zipfile.ZipFile(r'C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Downloads\\\\Deborah_Plain_Language_Record.docx'); xml=z.read('word/document.xml').decode('utf-8'); text=re.sub(r'<[^>]+>', '\\\\n', xml); text=re.sub(r'\\\\n+', '\\\\n', text); print(text[:8000])\\\" } else { Write-Host \\\"no python\\\" }\", \"description\": \"Convert Plain Language Record docx to text\"}",
      "output": "Add-Type : Impossibile aggiungere il tipo. L'assembly 'DocumentFormat.OpenXml' non � stato trovato.\r\nIn riga:1 car:7\r\n+ try { Add-Type -AssemblyName \"DocumentFormat.OpenXml\"; } catch {} ; i ...\r\n+       ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\r\n    + CategoryInfo          : ObjectNotFound: (DocumentFormat.OpenXml:String) [Add-Type], Exception\r\n    + FullyQualifiedErrorId : ASSEMBLY_NOT_FOUND,Microsoft.PowerShell.Commands.AddTypeCommand\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\r\nNHS Patient Medical Record\r\nPlain Language Guide for Mrs Deborah Ennin\r\nPatient:  Mrs Deborah Ennin     |     Practice:  Churchside Medical Practice\r\nPurpose:  Supporting evidence for PIP assessment\r\nDear Deborah,\r\nThis document is a plain-language explanation of your NHS medical records from Churchside Medical Practice. The original record uses a lot of medical words and numbers that can be confusing. This version goes through the same record, section by section, and explains in simple words what each entry means — what the doctors found, what the medicines do, and what the test results are telling us about your health.\r\nℹ️  How to use this document\r\n    Read it in order from the top. Each blue date heading matches a visit or test in your original NHS record.\r\n    The coloured boxes explain what things mean:\r\n       ℹ️  Blue box = general explanation\r\n       ⚠️  Yellow box = something the doctor was concerned about\r\n       ✅  Green box = a good result or positive news\r\nDecember 2025\r\n📅  5 December 2025 — Medicines renewed by Dr Haris Khan and the reception team\r\nOn this day, the doctor and one of the receptionists renewed all your regular prescription medicines. This is a routine thing the practice does — they check your medicines are still correct and make sure you can keep collecting them each month. Here is what each of your medicines does, in plain words:\r\nYour heart and blood pressure medicines:\r\nAmlodipine 10mg — This medicine relaxes and widens your blood vessels so that your heart does not have to work so hard to pump blood around your body. It helps to bring your blood pressure down.\r\nBisoprolol 2.5mg — This slows your heart down a little and makes it beat more steadily. It helps protect your heart after your heart attack in June 2024, and also helps with blood pressure.\r\nCandesartan 8mg — Another blood pressure medicine. It blocks a chemical in the body that makes blood vessels tight. Taking it at 6pm as instructed is important.\r\nAspirin 75mg — A low-dose aspirin to help thin your blood slightly. After a heart attack, doctors use aspirin to help stop blood clots forming in the heart's blood vessels. This is not for pain — it is a long-term heart medicine.\r\nYour diabetes medicines:\r\nSukkarto SR 500mg (Metformin) — Two tablets, twice a day. This is one of the most common diabetes medicines. It helps your body use the sugar in your blood more efficiently. The 'SR' means it is slow-release, so it is gentler on your stomach.\r\nGliclazide 80mg — Two tablets with breakfast and two with your evening tea. This medicine tells your pancreas (the organ that makes insulin) to produce more insulin. It is helping your body deal with sugar, but your records show it is struggling to keep your sugar levels under control on its own.\r\nEmpagliflozin 10mg (Ozempic is separate) — This is a tablet that makes your kidneys remove excess sugar from your blood by passing it out in your urine. It also helps protect your heart and kidneys.\r\nOzempic injection (Semaglutide 1mg) — This is a weekly injection that you give yourself in your stomach, thigh, or upper arm. It helps to control your blood sugar and also reduces your appetite and can help with weight. One pen lasts 4 weeks.\r\nYour cholesterol medicines:\r\nAtorvastatin 80mg — Taken at night (nocte). This medicine lowers the 'bad' fat (cholesterol) in your blood. High cholesterol causes fat to build up inside blood vessels, which can lead to heart attacks and strokes. This is the highest dose of this medicine.\r\nEzetimibe 10mg — Works alongside the atorvastatin to reduce cholesterol even further by stopping your gut from absorbing as much cholesterol from food.\r\nStomach protection:\r\nLansoprazole 15mg — Some of your other medicines (especially aspirin) can irritate your stomach lining. This capsule protects your stomach from acid and reduces the chance of stomach ulcers.\r\nBlood sugar testing supplies:\r\nCareSens lancets — The small needles used to prick your finger for blood sugar testing.\r\nGlucoMen Areo Sensor strips — The strips that go into your glucose meter to test your blood sugar level.\r\nSharpsafe disposal unit — The small yellow bin for safely throwing away used needles and lancets. Do not put these in the household bin — use this container.\r\nNovember 2025\r\n📅  21 November 2025 — Letter from the eye doctors\r\nThe practice received a letter from the eye specialist service. You had already been referred to them before, and this letter was confirming that they are continuing to look after you. No new action was needed from the GP surgery.\r\n📅  17 November 2025 — Diabetes review with Nurse Zoe Udall\r\nYou came to this appointment with your daughter, who was visiting from university. The nurse did a full check on how your diabetes is being managed. Unfortunately, the results at this visit were very worrying.\r\n⚠️  Your blood sugar level (HbA1c) was 145 mmol/mol — this is very high.\r\n    To understand this: a healthy person without diabetes has a level around 38–42.\r\n    For someone with diabetes, the target is usually 48–59.\r\n    Your level of 145 is nearly three times the target. This means your body has had\r\n    too much sugar in the blood for a long time, and the medicines are not controlling it well enough.\r\n    You had also gained 12kg (almost 2 stone) in weight since the last check.\r\nThe nurse noted that you were not eating much — just one meal a day — but were sleeping a lot. Eating only once a day actually makes diabetes harder to control, not easier, because your body then gets a very big sugar spike all at once. The nurse also noted that you were feeling thirsty often. This is a common sign that blood sugar is too high — the body tries to flush out the extra sugar by making you thirsty.\r\nThe nurse explained that your pancreas (the organ that makes insulin naturally) is becoming exhausted after so many years of working hard with diabetes. The tablets are doing as much as they can. The nurse told you that you really do need insulin injections now to properly control your sugar levels.\r\nℹ️  What the nurse recommended after this visit:\r\n    Refer you urgently to a Diabetes Specialist Nurse (DSN) to start insulin injections\r\n    Drink more fluids every day\r\n    Try to eat regular meals — at least two or three times a day, not just once\r\n    Increase gentle activity as much as possible\r\n    The Empagliflozin tablet may need to be stopped once insulin starts — the nurse raised a task about this\r\n    Influenza (flu) vaccination was also recommended — diabetes makes flu more dangerous\r\n📅  14 November 2025 — Medicines renewed (Dr Haris Khan)\r\nRoutine renewal of your blood sugar testing supplies and some of your regular tablets (Candesartan, Metformin, and the testing materials). Nothing new was added at this appointment.\r\n📅  5 November 2025 — Text message sent to you\r\nThe receptionist sent you a text message saying that your doctor had reviewed your recent test results and wanted you to make a routine appointment with the nurse to discuss them. This was the message that led to your appointment on 17 November.\r\nOctober 2025\r\n📅  28–29 October 2025 — Text messages sent to you\r\nThe reception team sent you two text messages in the days after your blood test results came back. Both messages were asking you to book an appointment to discuss the results with the nurse. These results are explained in the next section below.\r\n📅  27 October 2025 — Annual diabetes check and blood test results\r\nThis was your yearly full check-up for diabetes, done by a healthcare assistant called Elisha. They checked your feet, blood pressure, weight, and took blood samples. You also received your flu vaccine on this day.\r\nFoot check results\r\nYour feet were checked very carefully. This is very important for people with diabetes because high blood sugar over time can damage the nerves and blood vessels in the feet, meaning you might not feel pain if something is wrong. The good news is that your feet are in the 'low risk' category — there were no ulcers, no wounds, no deformity, and the feeling in both feet test\r\n",
