      "code": "{\"command\": \"python -c \\\"import zipfile, re; z=zipfile.ZipFile(r'C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Downloads\\\\Deborah_Plain_Language_Record.docx'); xml=z.read('word/document.xml').decode('utf-8'); text=re.sub(r'<[^>]+>', '\\\\n', xml); text=re.sub(r'\\\\n+', '\\\\n', text); print(text)\\\"\", \"description\": \"Extract full Plain Language Record text\"}",
      "output": "\r\n\r\r\nNHS Patient Medical Record\r\nPlain Language Guide for Mrs Deborah Ennin\r\nPatient:  Mrs Deborah Ennin     |     Practice:  Churchside Medical Practice\r\nPurpose:  Supporting evidence for PIP assessment\r\nDear Deborah,\r\nThis document is a plain-language explanation of your NHS medical records from Churchside Medical Practice. The original record uses a lot of medical words and numbers that can be confusing. This version goes through the same record, section by section, and explains in simple words what each entry means — what the doctors found, what the medicines do, and what the test results are telling us about your health.\r\nℹ️  How to use this document\r\n    Read it in order from the top. Each blue date heading matches a visit or test in your original NHS record.\r\n    The coloured boxes explain what things mean:\r\n       ℹ️  Blue box = general explanation\r\n       ⚠️  Yellow box = something the doctor was concerned about\r\n       ✅  Green box = a good result or positive news\r\nDecember 2025\r\n📅  5 December 2025 — Medicines renewed by Dr Haris Khan and the reception team\r\nOn this day, the doctor and one of the receptionists renewed all your regular prescription medicines. This is a routine thing the practice does — they check your medicines are still correct and make sure you can keep collecting them each month. Here is what each of your medicines does, in plain words:\r\nYour heart and blood pressure medicines:\r\nAmlodipine 10mg — This medicine relaxes and widens your blood vessels so that your heart does not have to work so hard to pump blood around your body. It helps to bring your blood pressure down.\r\nBisoprolol 2.5mg — This slows your heart down a little and makes it beat more steadily. It helps protect your heart after your heart attack in June 2024, and also helps with blood pressure.\r\nCandesartan 8mg — Another blood pressure medicine. It blocks a chemical in the body that makes blood vessels tight. Taking it at 6pm as instructed is important.\r\nAspirin 75mg — A low-dose aspirin to help thin your blood slightly. After a heart attack, doctors use aspirin to help stop blood clots forming in the heart's blood vessels. This is not for pain — it is a long-term heart medicine.\r\nYour diabetes medicines:\r\nSukkarto SR 500mg (Metformin) — Two tablets, twice a day. This is one of the most common diabetes medicines. It helps your body use the sugar in your blood more efficiently. The 'SR' means it is slow-release, so it is gentler on your stomach.\r\nGliclazide 80mg — Two tablets with breakfast and two with your evening tea. This medicine tells your pancreas (the organ that makes insulin) to produce more insulin. It is helping your body deal with sugar, but your records show it is struggling to keep your sugar levels under control on its own.\r\nEmpagliflozin 10mg (Ozempic is separate) — This is a tablet that makes your kidneys remove excess sugar from your blood by passing it out in your urine. It also helps protect your heart and kidneys.\r\nOzempic injection (Semaglutide 1mg) — This is a weekly injection that you give yourself in your stomach, thigh, or upper arm. It helps to control your blood sugar and also reduces your appetite and can help with weight. One pen lasts 4 weeks.\r\nYour cholesterol medicines:\r\nAtorvastatin 80mg — Taken at night (nocte). This medicine lowers the 'bad' fat (cholesterol) in your blood. High cholesterol causes fat to build up inside blood vessels, which can lead to heart attacks and strokes. This is the highest dose of this medicine.\r\nEzetimibe 10mg — Works alongside the atorvastatin to reduce cholesterol even further by stopping your gut from absorbing as much cholesterol from food.\r\nStomach protection:\r\nLansoprazole 15mg — Some of your other medicines (especially aspirin) can irritate your stomach lining. This capsule protects your stomach from acid and reduces the chance of stomach ulcers.\r\nBlood sugar testing supplies:\r\nCareSens lancets — The small needles used to prick your finger for blood sugar testing.\r\nGlucoMen Areo Sensor strips — The strips that go into your glucose meter to test your blood sugar level.\r\nSharpsafe disposal unit — The small yellow bin for safely throwing away used needles and lancets. Do not put these in the household bin — use this container.\r\nNovember 2025\r\n📅  21 November 2025 — Letter from the eye doctors\r\nThe practice received a letter from the eye specialist service. You had already been referred to them before, and this letter was confirming that they are continuing to look after you. No new action was needed from the GP surgery.\r\n📅  17 November 2025 — Diabetes review with Nurse Zoe Udall\r\nYou came to this appointment with your daughter, who was visiting from university. The nurse did a full check on how your diabetes is being managed. Unfortunately, the results at this visit were very worrying.\r\n⚠️  Your blood sugar level (HbA1c) was 145 mmol/mol — this is very high.\r\n    To understand this: a healthy person without diabetes has a level around 38–42.\r\n    For someone with diabetes, the target is usually 48–59.\r\n    Your level of 145 is nearly three times the target. This means your body has had\r\n    too much sugar in the blood for a long time, and the medicines are not controlling it well enough.\r\n    You had also gained 12kg (almost 2 stone) in weight since the last check.\r\nThe nurse noted that you were not eating much — just one meal a day — but were sleeping a lot. Eating only once a day actually makes diabetes harder to control, not easier, because your body then gets a very big sugar spike all at once. The nurse also noted that you were feeling thirsty often. This is a common sign that blood sugar is too high — the body tries to flush out the extra sugar by making you thirsty.\r\nThe nurse explained that your pancreas (the organ that makes insulin naturally) is becoming exhausted after so many years of working hard with diabetes. The tablets are doing as much as they can. The nurse told you that you really do need insulin injections now to properly control your sugar levels.\r\nℹ️  What the nurse recommended after this visit:\r\n    Refer you urgently to a Diabetes Specialist Nurse (DSN) to start insulin injections\r\n    Drink more fluids every day\r\n    Try to eat regular meals — at least two or three times a day, not just once\r\n    Increase gentle activity as much as possible\r\n    The Empagliflozin tablet may need to be stopped once insulin starts — the nurse raised a task about this\r\n    Influenza (flu) vaccination was also recommended — diabetes makes flu more dangerous\r\n📅  14 November 2025 — Medicines renewed (Dr Haris Khan)\r\nRoutine renewal of your blood sugar testing supplies and some of your regular tablets (Candesartan, Metformin, and the testing materials). Nothing new was added at this appointment.\r\n📅  5 November 2025 — Text message sent to you\r\nThe receptionist sent you a text message saying that your doctor had reviewed your recent test results and wanted you to make a routine appointment with the nurse to discuss them. This was the message that led to your appointment on 17 November.\r\nOctober 2025\r\n📅  28–29 October 2025 — Text messages sent to you\r\nThe reception team sent you two text messages in the days after your blood test results came back. Both messages were asking you to book an appointment to discuss the results with the nurse. These results are explained in the next section below.\r\n📅  27 October 2025 — Annual diabetes check and blood test results\r\nThis was your yearly full check-up for diabetes, done by a healthcare assistant called Elisha. They checked your feet, blood pressure, weight, and took blood samples. You also received your flu vaccine on this day.\r\nFoot check results\r\nYour feet were checked very carefully. This is very important for people with diabetes because high blood sugar over time can damage the nerves and blood vessels in the feet, meaning you might not feel pain if something is wrong. The good news is that your feet are in the 'low risk' category — there were no ulcers, no wounds, no deformity, and the feeling in both feet tested as normal using a special thin filament. The blood circulation in your feet was also present. This is good news — your feet are currently being well looked after.\r\n✅  Feet result: GOOD — Both feet are healthy, no wounds or nerve damage detected.\r\n    Your capillary refill time (how fast blood returns after pressing on the skin) was 4 seconds.\r\n    For reference: up to 2 seconds is considered ideal, but 3–5 seconds can be normal in some people.\r\nBlood pressure on this day\r\nYour blood pressure was recorded as 148/98 mmHg. Blood pressure is written as two numbers — like 148 over 98. The top number (148) is the pressure when your heart squeezes and pumps blood out. The bottom number (98) is the pressure when your heart is resting between beats. A healthy blood pressure target for someone with your health history is below 130/80. Your reading of 148/98 is above the target — meaning your heart is \r\nworking harder than it should be. This is why you are on several blood pressure tablets.\r\n⚠️  Blood pressure: 148/98 mmHg — This is too high.\r\n    Target: below 130/80 mmHg for someone with diabetes and a history of heart problems.\r\n    High blood pressure puts extra strain on your heart, kidneys, and blood vessels.\r\nWeight on this day\r\nYour weight was 110kg (approximately 17 stone 5 pounds). This is noted in the records and the doctors are concerned because excess weight makes diabetes harder to control and puts more strain on your heart.\r\nBlood test results — explained one by one\r\n🔬  Thyroid test (TSH):\r\n✅  Result: NORMAL — Your thyroid gland is working fine.\r\n    The thyroid is a small gland in your neck that controls how your body uses energy.\r\n    Your level was 0.81, which is comfortably inside the healthy range of 0.3–4.2.\r\n🔬  Kidney function test (Urea and Electrolytes):\r\nThis group of tests checks how well your kidneys are working and whether the salt balance in your body is correct.\r\nℹ️  Sodium: 135 — This is the level of salt in your blood. Yours is normal (range: 133–146).\r\n    Potassium: 4.0 — This is another important mineral in your blood. Yours is normal (range: 3.5–5.3).\r\n    Creatinine: 87 — A waste product the kidneys filter out. Yours is normal (range: 55–100).\r\n    Urea: 6.9 — Another waste product. Yours is normal (range: 2.5–7.8).\r\n    eGFR: 64 — This is the most important kidney number. It tells us how much blood\r\n    your kidneys are cleaning per minute. A healthy kidney filters &gt;90.\r\n    Your kidneys are working at about 64% of what a healthy kidney would do.\r\n    This puts you in a category called Chronic Kidney Disease Stage 2–3.\r\n    It means your kidneys need to be watched and protected — which is why some of your\r\n    medicines are chosen carefully to protect them.\r\n🔬  Blood sugar control (HbA1c):\r\n⚠️  HbA1c result: 145 mmol/mol — Very high. This is the most worrying result.\r\n    HbA1c tells us the AVERAGE blood sugar level over the past 3 months.\r\n    It is different from a finger-prick test, which only shows this one moment.\r\n    Healthy non-diabetic level: around 38–42 mmol/mol.\r\n    Diabetes target: 48–59 mmol/mol.\r\n    Your level of 145 means your blood has been carrying too much sugar every day\r\n    for a long time. This causes damage to blood vessels, nerves, eyes, and kidneys.\r\n    The lab also noted a 'possible variant Hb peak' — this is a minor technical note\r\n    about how your blood cells are built, but does not change the overall concern.\r\n🔬  Urine test (to check kidneys further — ACR):\r\nA urine test was done to check if any protein (albumin) is leaking from your kidneys into your urine. Healthy kidneys keep protein inside the blood. When they start to be damaged, protein leaks out.\r\n⚠️  Urine ACR: 4.1 mg/mmol — Slightly above the safe limit of &lt;3 mg/mmol.\r\n    This is classified as 'borderline microalbuminuria' — meaning a tiny amount of\r\n    protein is leaking out. The doctor said 'no further action' for now, but this is\r\n    something to watch. It means the kidneys are showing early signs of stress from the\r\n    long-standing high blood sugar and high blood pressure.\r\n🔬  Liver function tests:\r\nThese tests check how your liver is working and whether it is making the proteins your body needs.\r\n⚠️  Serum albumin: 31 g/L — This is BELOW the normal range (35–50 g/L).\r\n    Albumin is the main protein your liver makes to carry nutrients around your body.\r\n    A low albumin can mean your body is not getting enough nourishment, or that the\r\n    liver or kidneys are under stress. This has been low in several of your tests.\r\n    Other liver values (bilirubin, ALT, ALP) were all normal — so the liver itself\r\n    is not in serious trouble, but the albumin is something the doctors are watching.\r\n🔬  Cholesterol and fats in the blood (Lipids):\r\nCholesterol is a fatty substance in the blood. Too much of the wrong type blocks arteries (the pipes that carry blood to your heart and brain).\r\n⚠️  Total cholesterol: 6.3 mmol/L — High. Target for heart patients is below 4.0.\r\n    LDL ('bad') cholesterol: 4.0 mmol/L — High. Target is below 1.8 for heart patients.\r\n    HDL ('good') cholesterol: 1.1 mmol/L — Low-normal. We want this to be higher.\r\n    Triglycerides: 2.59 mmol/L — High. These are fats in your blood (target: below 1.5).\r\n    High triglycerides are linked to high sugar levels — when blood sugar is poorly\r\n    controlled, the liver makes more triglycerides.\r\n    Despite being on strong cholesterol medicines, these levels are still too high,\r\n    which is partly because the diabetes itself raises fat levels in the blood.\r\n🔬  Full blood count (checking your blood cells):\r\nThis test counts the different types of cells in your blood — red blood cells (which carry oxygen), white blood cells (which fight infection), and platelets (which help blood clot).\r\nℹ️  Haemoglobin: 126 g/L — This is within the normal range for women (115–160). Good.\r\n    MCV: 81.6 fL — Slightly below normal (83–103). This measures the SIZE of your red cells.\r\n    MCH: 26.7 pg — Slightly below normal (27–35). This measures the COLOUR of your red cells.\r\n    Small, pale red blood cells (low MCV and MCH) can be a sign of iron deficiency anaemia.\r\n    White blood cells and platelets: Both normal. No sign of infection or clotting problems.\r\n    The doctor filed this as 'Normal, No Further Action' overall, but the slightly\r\n    low MCV and MCH are worth monitoring.\r\n🔬  Total protein:\r\nThis measures all the protein in your blood combined. Your result was 74 g/L, which is within the normal range (60–80). The doctor was slightly concerned and wanted to discuss, but this is not far outside normal.\r\nEye-related letter also received on 27 October 2025\r\nOn the same day, the practice also received a report from an optician (GOS18 report). This showed that you have been found to have raised pressure inside your eyes (called glaucoma) and some cupping of the optic nerve (which is linked to glaucoma). You have been referred to an eye specialist. This is explained in more detail in the eyes section later in this document.\r\n📅  20 October 2025 — Missed appointment\r\nThe record shows you did not attend a scheduled appointment on this day. Sometimes this happens — life gets in the way, or on some days the illness itself makes it hard to leave the house.\r\n📅  14 October 2025 — Medicine templates authorised by Dr Claire Harrison\r\nThis was an administrative step where Dr Harrison reviewed and approved the list of your regular medicines, so that they could be re-issued. The same medicines as usual were continued.\r\nNovember 2024\r\n📅  18 November 2024 — Face-to-face appointment with Dr Claire Harrison\r\nYou came in to discuss your diabetes treatment. At this point, your HbA1c (blood sugar average) was 131 mmol/mol — still very high, though slightly lower than it became by October 2025.\r\nYou told the doctor you had not been using the Ozempic injection for about a month because you had forgotten to collect it from the pharmacy. You were taking your other tablets correctly (in a blister pack), but your blood sugar level (BM 16.8) when the doctor tested you that day was very high. A BM reading of 16.8 mmol/L means there was a lot of sugar in your blood. For reference, a healthy blood sugar reading before eating is usually 4–7 mmol/L.\r\nThe doctor offered you insulin injections, which is the next step when tablets are no longer enough. You said you would prefer not to start insulin — you wanted to try restarting the Ozempic injection instead. The doctor agreed to restart Ozempic and asked you to check your blood sugar once a day and come back in two weeks.\r\nℹ️  Plan agreed on 18 November 2024:\r\n    Restart Ozempic injection\r\n    Check blood sugar with your monitor once every day\r\n    Return in 2 weeks for a follow-up\r\n    Provide a urine sample to check for ketones (a sign of very uncontrolled diabetes)\r\n📅  15 November 2024 — Diabetes review with Nurse Keris Rhodes\r\nThe nurse had a very long and detailed conversation with you about your diabetes. The main message from this appointment was serious: the nurse told you that you urgently needed insulin injections to properly control your diabetes, because the tablets had reached their limit in what they can do.\r\nYou had been hesitant about insulin for a while. The nurse noted in the records that she understood this was because you cared for your late husband when he was on insulin, and that experience was difficult and upsetting for you. This is very understandable — watching a loved one struggle with illness leaves a deep mark on us. However, the nurse gently explained that insulin for you is different: your husband's situation was his own, and starting insulin now would help you feel much better, not worse.\r\nThe nurse also gave you a new blood sugar monitor because you could not find your old one. She asked you to test your blood sugar before breakfast and before your evening meal. She also talked to you about your diet. You told her your typical meals were smoothies (banana, strawberry, apple, kiwi) for breakfast or porridge with toast, and rice, meat and vegetables, plantain, yam, or fish for the evening. The nurse explained that while these are wholesome foods, some of them — especially white rice, plantain, yam, and bread — are high in starchy carbohydrates that the body quickly turns into sugar. Reducing portion sizes of these foods, or replacing some with lower-carb alternatives, can help control blood sugar.\r\n⚠️  The nurse was concerned that your mental health and grief around your husband's death\r\n    may be making it harder for you to manage your health and accept treatment.\r\n    She noted this in the records. This is not a criticism — it is the nurse recognising\r\n    that caring for yourself when you are grieving or low in spirit is very hard.\r\nOctober–November 2024 (Blood Tests and Cardiology)\r\n📅  25 October 2024 — Blood pressure check and cardiology letter\r\nYour blood pressure was found to be 168/110 mmHg — this is quite high. Remember: for context, a healthy target is below 130/80. A reading of 168/110 means your heart is under a lot of extra strain. The nurse called Dr Ahmad to inform him, and you were asked to monitor your blood pressure at home and book a GP appointment for the following week.\r\nOn the same day, a letter arrived from the Cardiology department (the heart specialists). The letter noted that you were unable to attend a cardiology assessment because of fatigue and pain in your legs. Because of this, the practice referred you to a Health and Wellbeing Coach — someone who can support you at home.\r\nAlso on this day, you received two vaccinations at the pharmacy: your COVID-19 booster and your yearly flu vaccine. Well done for getting those done.\r\nℹ️  Blood test results from around this time:\r\n    Iron stores (transferrin, ferritin, serum iron): All within normal range.\r\n    Reticulocyte count: Normal — this checks that your bone marrow is making new red\r\n    blood cells properly. Yours is doing fine.\r\nSeptember 2024\r\n📅  23 September 2024 — Annual diabetes review with Dr Rachel Hibberd\r\nYou came to this appointment with your son. Dr Hibberd reviewed how your diabetes was going. At this point your HbA1c was 126 mmol/mol — still very high, and the record notes it had been over 100 for two years.\r\nThe doctor noted that you had been seen by diabetes nurses when you were in hospital for your heart attack in June 2024 (more about that below), and that at that time you had again declined insulin injections. You had also lost your glucose monitor and had not been testing your blood sugar.\r\nThe doctor had a long discussion with you and explained the serious risks of poorly controlled diabetes: another stroke, another heart attack, possible limb loss, loss of sight, and kidney damage. After this discussion, you said you still did not want insulin and wished to continue with your current medicines including Ozempic. The doctor respected your decision (you have the right to make your own choices) and agreed to increase your Metformin to the maximum dose of 1g twice daily, and to repeat your HbA1c blood test in 3 months. A new glucose meter was given to you.\r\n⚠️  Your BMI at this visit was 38.57 kg/m² (weight: 105kg, height: 1.65m).\r\n    BMI is a rough measure comparing weight to height. A healthy BMI is 18.5–24.9.\r\n    A BMI of 38.57 is in the 'obese' range. Excess weight makes diabetes much harder\r\n    to control and puts extra pressure on your heart, joints, and kidneys.\r\n    This is not about appearance — it is about what is happening inside your body.\r\n📅  19 September 2024 — Blood pressure review with Dr Nayab Malik\r\nYour blood pressure was recorded as 164/102 mmHg — too high. You had no symptoms on this day (no headache, chest pain, or breathlessness), but the doctor was still concerned because of your history of stroke and heart attack. The doctor increased your Bisoprolol dose from 1.25mg to 2.5mg to try to bring the blood pressure down.\r\n📅  17 September 2024 — Foot check and blood tests\r\nAnother detailed foot check was done. Again, the results were good — both feet healthy, no ulcers or wounds, normal sensation. However, blood pressure readings at this visit were very high:\r\n⚠️  Blood pressure readings: 192/110, then 180/114, then 170/116 mmHg.\r\n    These readings are seriously elevated. The nurse informed Dr Harrison immediately.\r\n    Home blood pressure monitoring was requested to track this at home.\r\nBlood test results from 17 September 2024:\r\nℹ️  eGFR (kidney filtering): 67 mL/min — Kidneys working at about 67%. Watched carefully.\r\n    Albumin: 32 g/L — Below normal (35–50). Low protein in the blood (also seen in later tests).\r\n    Triglycerides: 2.64 mmol/L — High fats in the blood, linked to poor sugar control.\r\n    Haemoglobin: 118 g/L — Slightly below normal for women (120–150). Possible mild anaemia.\r\n    MCV: 78 fL, MCH: 25.7 pg — Red blood cells slightly small and pale. Possible iron shortage.\r\n    Urine ACR: 5.2 mg/mmol — Protein leaking in urine. Above the safe limit of &lt;3. Kidney stress.\r\nAugust 2024 — Eye specialist letter\r\n📅  30 August 2024 — Letter from eye doctors (Ophthalmology)\r\nA letter arrived from the eye specialists reporting on a check they had done on your eyes. Diabetes can affect the blood vessels at the back of the eye (the retina), and this needs regular checking.\r\n⚠️  Findings:\r\n    Bilateral early cortical cataracts — Both eyes have the early stages of cataracts.\r\n    A cataract is when the lens of the eye becomes cloudy, making vision blurry.\r\n    'Early' means it has not yet reached the stage where treatment is needed.\r\n    \r\n    Mild non-proliferative diabetic retinopathy with early maculopathy — Both eyes.\r\n    Retinopathy means the tiny blood vessels at the back of the eye are being damaged\r\n    by the high blood sugar. 'Non-proliferative' means it is in the early stage —\r\n    no new abnormal blood vessels are growing yet. But the macula (the central part of\r\n    the eye that gives you sharp vision) is also showing early signs of involvement.\r\n    'Hard exudates' in the right macula: these are small deposits of fat and protein\r\n    that have leaked from damaged blood vessels.\r\n    Follow-up in 4 months was recommended.\r\nJuly 2024 — Blood Tests\r\n📅  30 July 2024 — Blood test results\r\nThese blood tests were taken a few weeks after your heart attack (June 2024). Here is what they showed:\r\n⚠️  HbA1c: 102 mmol/mol — Blood sugar average still very high (target: 48–59).\r\n    Albumin: 34 g/L — Still slightly below normal (range: 35–50).\r\n    Triglycerides: 1.84 mmol/L — Slightly above normal (target: below 1.5).\r\n    Ferritin: 249 ng/mL — Ferritin stores iron. This is ABOVE normal (13–150).\r\n    Raised ferritin can sometimes be linked to inflammation, liver stress, or other\r\n    conditions. The doctor would have been aware of this.\r\n    Vitamin B12: 1,237 ng/L — Above normal (197–771). High B12 can sometimes occur\r\n    when the body is under stress or when there is liver activity. It is not usually\r\n    harmful but is something to be aware of.\r\n    MCV: 78 fL — Red blood cells still slightly small (pattern consistent with earlier tests).\r\nJune 2024 — Heart Attack and Hospital\r\n📅  26 June 2024 — Ambulance called for chest pain\r\nAn ambulance was called because you had chest pain. You were taken to the hospital.\r\n📅  29 June 2024 — Hospital discharge summary (Heart attack)\r\nThis is the hospital's formal letter summarising what happened during your hospital stay. This was one of the most serious events in your recent medical history.\r\n⚠️  Diagnosis: STEMI — ST-elevation Myocardial Infarction (a type of heart attack).\r\n    What this means: One of the blood vessels supplying your heart (the circumflex artery)\r\n    became completely blocked. When blood cannot reach part of the heart muscle,\r\n    that part starts to die. This is a medical emergency.\r\n    \r\n    Treatment: PCI (Percutaneous Coronary Intervention)\r\n    Doctors inserted a very thin tube (catheter) through a blood vessel, guided it to the\r\n    blocked artery in your heart, and opened it up. They also placed a drug-eluting stent\r\n    — a tiny metal mesh tube — inside the artery to keep it open.\r\n    A drug-eluting stent releases medicine slowly to stop the artery from blocking again.\r\n    \r\n    Also found: Atherosclerosis in the LAD artery (another heart artery).\r\n    Atherosclerosis means fatty deposits have built up inside that artery too.\r\n    The LAD was not fully blocked but will need continued monitoring and medicines.\r\nThe hospital also noted that your diabetes control was very poor (HbA1c over 100) and that insulin was offered but you declined at that time.\r\nAfter the heart attack, new medicines were started or adjusted:\r\nAspirin 75mg — Started to protect the new stent from blood clots\r\nClopidogrel 75mg — Another blood-thinning medicine. Works alongside aspirin to protect the stent. The hospital said to stop this after 12 months.\r\nEzetimibe 10mg — Started to further lower cholesterol\r\nGlyceryl trinitrate (GTN) spray — Emergency spray for chest pain. Spray under the tongue if chest pain comes on.\r\nLansoprazole 15mg — Stomach protector\r\nBisoprolol reduced to 1.25mg; Candesartan 8mg once daily\r\nGliclazide increased to 160mg twice daily to try to improve blood sugar\r\nFollow-up was arranged with the heart clinic in Nottingham (ACS clinic), an echocardiogram (ultrasound of the heart) was requested for 3 months later, and a diabetic nurse review was also planned.\r\nJanuary–March 2025\r\n📅  18 January 2025 — Brain MRI scan\r\nYou had an MRI scan of your head because you had been having severe headaches at the front of your head for about a month, along with nausea. An MRI uses magnetic fields to take detailed pictures of the inside of your body — it does not use X-rays.\r\n✅  MRI result: No new problems found. Normal result for your situation.\r\n    The scan showed the existing area of damage from your 2020 stroke (the PICA territory\r\n    infarct in the back-right part of the brain — the cerebellum). This is already known.\r\n    There was also mild 'microvascular disease' — this means the very tiny blood vessels in\r\n    the brain show small signs of age-related wear and tear, which is common.\r\n    No tumour, no collection of blood, no new stroke was found.\r\n    The headaches did not have a serious cause shown on the scan.\r\n📅  4 March 2025 — Fall down stairs and rib injury\r\nYou fell down the stairs over the weekend and injured your right side. You went to A&amp;E and were sent home with advice. You then came to see Dr Ravi Patni at the surgery because you were still in pain.\r\nThe doctor examined you. Your breathing was fine (oxygen levels were 99%, which is excellent). There was tenderness (pain when pressed) over the lower right ribs, but no crackling noise (crepitus), no bruising visible, and good air entry in both lungs. This suggested bruised or cracked ribs — painful, but not life-threatening.\r\nℹ️  Diagnosis: Chest wall injury (likely bruised or cracked ribs from the fall)\r\n    Treatment: Co-codamol 30/500 (a painkiller combining paracetamol and codeine)\r\n    to be taken as needed, up to 8 tablets in 24 hours. Continue ibuprofen as well.\r\n    Review in 2 weeks.\r\n    Note: Falls are concerning for someone with your history of stroke and balance issues.\r\n    The record also notes that you attended A&amp;E on 1 March 2025 for this fall.\r\nYour Eyes — Ongoing follow-up (2024–2025)\r\nYour eyes have been under regular review because diabetes can damage the blood vessels at the back of the eye over time. Here is a summary of the eye follow-up appointments in order:\r\n📅  30 August 2024 — Eye specialist: early cataracts and early retinopathy found (see August section above)\r\nRecall: Both eyes showing early cataracts (cloudy lens) and mild diabetic retinopathy (blood vessel damage at the back of the eye). Follow-up arranged.\r\n📅  7 March 2025 — Eye clinic: new finding — macular oedema in left eye\r\nAt this visit, the eye doctors found that the left eye now had something called diabetic macular oedema — this means fluid is building up in the central part of the retina (the macula) of the left eye. The macula is the part that gives you your sharp, central vision.\r\n⚠️  Diabetic macular oedema (left eye): This is a new, more serious development.\r\n    Fluid build-up in the macula can cause blurred or distorted central vision.\r\n    It is caused by the high blood sugar damaging blood vessel walls, making them leaky.\r\n    The right eye did not show this problem at this stage.\r\n    Follow-up was arranged for 3 months.\r\n📅  28 May 2025 — Eye clinic: intraocular pressure check\r\nThis visit focused on the pressure inside your eyes (intraocular pressure — IOP). High eye pressure is associated with a condition called glaucoma, which can damage the optic nerve and eventually cause loss of side vision.\r\nℹ️  Finding: Borderline intraocular pressure — not severely high, but being watched.\r\n    An OCT scan (Optical Coherence Tomography) was done — this is a special camera\r\n    scan that takes cross-section pictures of the layers of the retina.\r\n    Follow-up: 12 months for further IOP and visual field checks.\r\n📅  27 October 2025 — Glaucoma formally diagnosed\r\nBased on the optician's GOS18 report, glaucoma and optic cupping were formally recorded in your medical notes, and a referral to an ophthalmologist (eye hospital specialist) was made.\r\n⚠️  Glaucoma: This is a condition where the optic nerve (the nerve connecting the eye\r\n    to the brain) is damaged, often due to raised pressure inside the eye.\r\n    Optic cupping: This refers to changes in the shape of the optic nerve — a sign that\r\n    the nerve may be under pressure.\r\n    Glaucoma can be managed with eye drops and monitoring, but needs specialist care.\r\n    You are now being followed up by the eye hospital team.\r\nSummary Table — Your Key Health Numbers Over Time\r\nThis table shows how some of your most important health numbers have changed over time. This is the same table as in your original NHS record, but with explanations added.\r\nHbA1c = average blood sugar (target: 48–59).  eGFR = how well kidneys work (higher is better).  BP = blood pressure (target below 130/80).\r\nDate\r\nHbA1c\r\neGFR (Kidneys)\r\nBlood Pressure\r\nWeight\r\nFeb 2023\r\n125 — High\r\n85 — Good\r\n—\r\n—\r\nJun 2023\r\n124 — High\r\n—\r\n152/90 — High\r\n107 kg\r\nAug 2023\r\n111 — High\r\n50 — Low\r\n139/83 — High\r\n—\r\nOct 2023\r\n112 — High\r\n64 — Low\r\n162/110 — !!\r\n108 kg\r\nJul 2024\r\n102 — High\r\n79 — OK\r\n—\r\n110 kg\r\nSep 2024\r\n126 — High\r\n67 — Low\r\n170/116 — !!\r\n105 kg\r\nNov 2024\r\n131 — High\r\n76 — OK\r\n139/86 — High\r\n—\r\nJan 2025\r\n71 — Better\r\n—\r\n136/86 — High\r\n—\r\nOct 2025\r\n145 — Highest\r\n64 — Low\r\n148/98 — High\r\n110 kg\r\nThe orange-highlighted cells show dates when the readings were especially concerning. You can see that January 2025 had a much better HbA1c of 71 — this shows that when medicines are working well, your body CAN respond. The key is consistency.\r\nYour Full Medicine List (as at December 2025)\r\nHere is every medicine you are currently prescribed, in plain language, with a simple explanation of why you are taking each one.\r\nMedicine\r\nWhat it is for\r\nWhy YOU take it\r\nAmlodipine 10mg\r\nLowers blood pressure\r\nYour blood pressure is too high. This widens blood vessels.\r\nAspirin 75mg\r\nPrevents blood clots\r\nAfter your heart attack and stent, this protects the stent from clotting.\r\nAtorvastatin 80mg\r\nLowers cholesterol\r\nYour cholesterol is high. Taken at night. High-dose to protect your heart.\r\nBisoprolol 2.5mg\r\nSlows and steadies the heart\r\nProtects your heart after the heart attack. Also lowers blood pressure.\r\nCandesartan 8mg\r\nLowers blood pressure\r\nTaken at 6pm. Also helps protect your kidneys from diabetes damage.\r\nEmpagliflozin 10mg\r\nRemoves sugar through urine\r\nHelps lower blood sugar and also protects the heart and kidneys.\r\nEzetimibe 10mg\r\nLowers cholesterol (from food)\r\nWorks with atorvastatin to further reduce bad cholesterol.\r\nGliclazide 80mg\r\nMakes pancreas produce insulin\r\n2 tablets with breakfast, 2 with evening tea. Helps manage blood sugar.\r\nLansoprazole 15mg\r\nProtects stomach lining\r\nSome of your medicines (especially aspirin) can irritate your stomach.\r\nOzempic injection\r\nControls blood sugar + weight\r\nWeekly injection. Reduces blood sugar and appetite. Very important.\r\nSukkarto SR 500mg (Metformin)\r\nHelps body use blood sugar\r\n2 tablets twice daily. A key diabetes medicine. Slow-release.\r\nCareSens lancets\r\nFinger-prick needles\r\nTo prick your finger for blood sugar testing.\r\nGlucoMen strips\r\nBlood sugar test strips\r\nGoes in your meter to measure your blood sugar level.\r\nSharpsafe 1L bin\r\nSafe needle disposal\r\nDispose of used lancets and needles safely. Do not use the household bin.\r\nAll Your Diagnoses — Plain Language Explanation\r\nThese are all the conditions that are officially recorded in your medical notes, with a simple explanation of each one.\r\nType 2 Diabetes Mellitus — Poorly controlled\r\nDiabetes is a condition where your body either does not make enough insulin, or cannot use insulin properly. Insulin is the key that lets sugar from food enter your body's cells. Without insulin working well, sugar builds up in the blood. Over many years of high blood sugar, it damages blood vessels, nerves, eyes, kidneys, and the heart. Your records show your blood sugar has been persistently very high (over 100 mmol/mol, often 120–145) for several years, despite maximum doses of several medicines. This is why insulin is now being strongly recommended.\r\nHeart attack (STEMI) — June 2024\r\nYou had a serious heart attack in June 2024 where one of the blood vessels to your heart (the circumflex artery) was completely blocked. You were treated with a procedure that opened the blockage and placed a stent inside to keep the artery open. You are taking several medicines now specifically because of this event.\r\nAtherosclerosis (hardening of the arteries)\r\nFatty deposits (plaque) have built up inside some of your arteries, including one called the LAD (left anterior descending) artery which supplies the front of your heart. This is the same process that caused your heart attack. Your cholesterol and blood pressure medicines help to stop it from getting worse.\r\nCerebellar stroke — 2020 (PICA territory infarct)\r\nYou had a stroke in 2020. A stroke happens when blood supply to part of the brain is cut off, and part of the brain is damaged. Yours affected the cerebellum — the part of the brain at the back that controls balance and coordination. This is why you have had balance problems and use a walking stick since then.\r\nHypertension (high blood pressure)\r\nYour blood pressure has been high for a long time and has needed several different medicines to try to control it. High blood pressure is a major risk factor for strokes and heart attacks, both of which you have already experienced.\r\nDiabetic retinopathy and macular oedema\r\nDiabetic retinopathy means the blood vessels at the back of your eye have been damaged by the high blood sugar. The macula (the central, sharpest \r\npart of your vision) in the left eye now has fluid build-up (oedema). This is being managed by the eye hospital team.\r\nGlaucoma and optic cupping\r\nGlaucoma is a condition where raised pressure inside the eye damages the optic nerve. The optic nerve connects your eye to your brain. Optic cupping is an early visible sign of this damage. You are now under the care of eye specialists for this.\r\nBilateral early cortical cataracts\r\nBoth eyes have early-stage cataracts — clouding of the lens inside the eye. This has not yet needed treatment, but it is being watched.\r\nChronic kidney disease (CKD)\r\nYour kidneys are not filtering blood as well as they should be (eGFR has ranged from 50–85 over the past two years). Diabetes and high blood pressure are the two most common causes of kidney damage. Your medicines are chosen carefully to protect your kidneys as much as possible.\r\nHigh cholesterol (Hyperlipidaemia)\r\nYour blood contains too much cholesterol, particularly the harmful type (LDL). You are already on the highest doses of two cholesterol-lowering medicines (Atorvastatin and Ezetimibe). The difficulty is that poor diabetes control itself raises fat levels in the blood.\r\nLow albumin (Hypoalbuminaemia)\r\nYour albumin level (the main protein made by the liver to carry nutrients around the body) has been consistently below normal across several blood tests. This can be a sign that your body's nutrition or protein absorption needs attention.\r\nMicrocytic anaemia (small, pale red blood cells)\r\nSeveral blood tests have shown that your red blood cells are slightly smaller and paler than normal (low MCV and MCH). This pattern often points to iron deficiency — not enough iron in the body to make healthy red blood cells. Iron helps your blood carry oxygen. Anaemia can cause tiredness, breathlessness, and feeling cold.\r\nBack/leg pain (Radiculopathy/Sciatica)\r\nYou have been dealing with pain down your back and leg, which is related to a nerve being irritated or pressed in the lower back. Combined with the effects of your stroke on your balance, this contributes to your difficulty walking and why you use a walking stick.\r\nModerate frailty\r\nThis was recorded in April 2023. Frailty in medical terms does not mean 'fragile' in a dismissive way — it is a clinical assessment that recognises when someone has reduced physical reserves, is more vulnerable to illness or accidents, and may need extra support. This is particularly relevant for your PIP application.\r\nObesity\r\nYour BMI has ranged between approximately 38–40 over the past two years. A BMI above 30 is classified as obese in medical terms. This puts additional strain on your heart, joints, and makes diabetes harder to control.\r\nA Final Word\r\nDeborah, your medical records show that you are dealing with many serious health conditions all at the same time — diabetes, a history of stroke and heart attack, high blood pressure, eye problems, kidney strain, and more. Managing all of these together is a very heavy burden.\r\nThe records also show that your medical team at Churchside Practice cares about you and has been working hard to try to help you. They understand that some of your decisions around insulin may be connected to the pain of caring for your late husband. If you ever want to talk to someone about how grief and illness are affecting you, that is something the practice or a counsellor can also help with.\r\nThe most important thing your doctors want you to know is this: starting insulin would likely make you feel significantly better. Your blood sugar level of 145 is causing you to feel tired, thirsty, and low in energy. Bringing that level down — even to 80 or 90 — could change how you feel day to day.\r\n✅  If you have questions about anything in this document, bring it to your next appointment\r\n    and the nurse or doctor can go through it with you. You can also bring a family member\r\n    or friend to help you remember what is discussed.\r\nThis is an unofficial plain-language explanation of NHS records.\r\nThe clinical content has not been altered. © Crown copyright\r\nChurchside Medical Practice | NHS Nottingham and Nottinghamshire ICB — 52R\r\n\r\n",
