      "type": "user-query",
      "text": "is this is the situation we are in do u kno wthe answer..\n\nLet me search for your father first, then I'll tackle everything else.Okay, that's significant. Here's what I found on Godfried, and then I'll work through everything else.\n\nYour father's conditions:\n\nFrom his death certificate and medical records discussed in previous conversations:\n\nHypertension — documented from at least May 2012, on six hypertensive medications\n\nDiabetes\n\nEnd-stage renal disease — diagnosed August 2015, was being assessed for kidney transplant list\n\nDementia — emerging in later years\n\nPassed away May 2022\n\nWhy this matters for your mum right now:\n\nThe combination your father had — hypertension + diabetes + kidney disease — is called diabetic nephropathy, and it's one of the most common progression paths for poorly controlled T2D. Your mum already has hypertension. Her HbA1c was critically high for two years. Her kidneys need to be on your radar now, not later. Has anyone checked her kidney function (eGFR) recently? Because that's the silent progression nobody talks about until it's advanced.\n\nOn uploading her Libre data to the NHS portal:\n\nYes, do this. The Libre generates PDF reports through the LibreView platform — you create an account at libreview.com, link her sensor data, and it produces a time-in-range report that GPs and diabetes nurses actually use. You can then:\n\nUpload it to her NHS record via the NHS App\n\nOr email it directly to her GP surgery as an attachment\n\nThis is entirely within your rights as her carer and it absolutely accelerates clinical decisions. You're not overstepping — you're doing the system's job for it.\n\nLibreLinkUp — what it is and your setup ideas:\n\nLibreLinkUp is Abbott's companion app. Once she scans with the LibreLink app on her phone, you get her readings in real time on yours. Simple to set up — she just adds you as a connection in the app.\n\nYour AKCloud / TV / Alexa ideas are genuinely doable:\n\nLibreView has an API — you could pull her glucose data into a dashboard on AKCloud\n\nSamsung Smart TV — a simple web app displaying her current reading and trend arrow, always visible in the living room\n\nAlexa — a routine that reads out her glucose level on demand, or alerts if it goes above/below thresholds\n\nThat's not a complicated build for you. Want me to sketch the architecture?\n\nHep B and diabetes — why it matters:\n\nChronic Hepatitis B affects the liver. The liver is central to glucose metabolism — it's where glucose is stored and released. So:\n\nIt can cause blood sugar to be unpredictably high or low\n\nIt limits which diabetes medications are safe — specifically metformin requires good liver function, so if her Hep B is active rather than stable, her medication options narrow\n\nThe discharge summary said her Hep B was stable — but that needs monitoring alongside her diabetes, not separately\n\nGI — Glycaemic Index:\n\nIt's a measure of how fast a food raises blood sugar. High GI = fast spike. Low GI = slow steady rise.\n\nGhanaian staples:\n\nWhite rice — high GI (fast spike)\n\nPlantain — medium to high depending on ripeness, riper = higher\n\nFufu — high GI\n\nBanku — high GI\n\nYam — medium GI, actually better than rice\n\nKenkey — medium GI, fermentation helps slightly\n\nThis doesn't mean she can't eat them. It means portion size and pairing matter — eating rice with a lot of protein and fat slows the spike significantly.\n\nSigns of a hypo and what to do:\n\nA hypo is blood glucose below 4 mmol/L. Symptoms:\n\nShakiness, trembling\n\nSweating suddenly\n\nHeart racing\n\nConfusion or difficulty concentrating\n\nPale skin\n\nHunger suddenly intense\n\nIrritability or unusual mood\n\nIn worse cases — slurred speech, difficulty standing, loss of consciousness\n\nWhat to do immediately:\n\n15g fast-acting carbs — 150ml fruit juice, 4-5 glucose tablets, or a small regular Coke (not diet)\n\nWait 15 minutes, recheck the Libre\n\nIf still below 4, repeat\n\nOnce above 4, give a small starchy snack to stabilise\n\nCritical for her specifically — because she's on cardiac beta-blockers post-STEMI, they can mask the shaking and racing heart symptoms. She might feel confused or just \"off\" without the classic physical warning signs. So the Libre reading is your early warning system, not her symptoms.\n\nIf she's unconscious or can't swallow — call 999 immediately, do not try to give food or drink.\n\nThat's a lot but every single one of those threads connects directly to her situation right now. Which one do you want to go deeper on first?\n\n<system-reminder>\n<agent-context>\n  agent: Mavis\n  agentName: mavis\n  SESSION ROLE: root\n  YOUR SESSION ID: mvs_843613dcd7384893945e4eb788488d09\n  YOUR AGENT ROOT SESSION: mvs_d12969f76d564c59a7d5be05b0fd5bdf\n  YOUR WORKSPACE DIRECTORY: C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\.mavis\\sessions\\mvs_843613dcd7384893945e4eb788488d09\\workspace\n  IS_DEFAULT_WORKSPACE: true\n  date: 2026-06-22 17:18:33 (Europe/London, UTC+1)\n</agent-context>\n\n<windows-behavior>\nReminder — your shell is PowerShell, NOT bash. Do NOT use `&&`, `ls -la`,\n`head`, `tail`, `grep`, `wc`. Use `;`, `Get-ChildItem`, `Select-Object`,\n`Select-String` instead. If `bash` produces garbled/WSL output, switch to\n`node`/`python` immediately — max 2 retries before changing approach.\n</windows-behavior>\n\n<user_profile_missing>\nYou don't know this user well enough yet — their profile is missing or too thin.\nYou may have chatted before, but you may lack basic context (name, role, work focus) to tailor your help.\n\n## Goal\nFill in the gaps naturally. Learn enough about them to be genuinely useful over time.\n\n## Strategy\n- **They're just chatting / greeting:** Good moment to learn about them. Weave in\n  1–2 light questions — but match their energy, not an interview.\n- **They gave you a task:** Do the task first, do it well. After delivering,\n  slip in a casual question if it flows naturally. If it feels forced, skip it — next time.\n\n## Tone\nCurious colleague, not onboarding form. Keep it to ONE question per turn at most. Examples:\n- \"搞定了～ 对了，你平时主要做哪块的？后面我好更有针对性地帮你\"\n- \"方便的话简单说说你的角色和关注点？这样我后面能更贴合你的场景\"\n\nDon't assume it's a first meeting — they may already know you. Avoid stiff self-introductions\nunless they clearly don't know what you are. Never ask multiple profile questions in one turn.\nNever ask about something you already know from conversation history or prior context.\n\nOnce you learn something, append it to C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\.mavis\\memory\\user.md.\n</user_profile_missing>\n</system-reminder>",
